File:We Stay Home logo by the Hellenic Ministry of Health during the 2019-20 coronavirus pandemic.png|thumb|Logo of the \"\u039c\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bc\u03b5 \u03a3\u03c0\u03af\u03c4\u03b9\" (We Stay Home) campaign by the Hellenic Ministry of Health]]\n[[File:COVID19 - Cell alert.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Cell Broadcast|Cell Broadcast Message]] sent on all smartphones in Greece on March 11 by the General Secretariat for Civil Protection, with general instructions regarding the pandemic]]\nThe [[Greek Government]] has announced the following measures:<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Restrictions on movements and gatherings ===\nOn 9 March, all school trips were banned, all sports games were to be played with no fans attending and all school championships were cancelled,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ieidiseis.gr/ellada/item/37553-koronoios-stin-ellada-epta-nea-kroysmata-stous-73-oi-astheneis|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u0395\u03c0\u03c4\u03ac \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 - \u03a3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 73 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c3\u03b8\u03b5\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03c2 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bd\u03bf\u03c3\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd|date=8 March 2020|website=ieidiseis|language=el|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> and starting on 10 March, all educational institutions were closed for 14 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minedu.gov.gr/news/44308-10-03-20-prosorini-apagorefsi-tis-ekpaideftikis-leitourgias-olon-ton-ekpaideftikon-domon|title=\u03a5\u03a0\u039f\u03a5\u03a1\u0393\u0395\u0399\u039f \u03a0\u0391\u0399\u0394\u0395\u0399\u0391\u03a3 & \u0398\u03a1\u0397\u03a3\u039a\u0395\u03a5\u039c\u0391\u03a4\u03a9\u039d - 10-03-20 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b5\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03cc\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03ba\u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u03b4\u03bf\u03bc\u03ce\u03bd|date=10 March 2020|website=\u03a5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b5\u03af\u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0398\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd|language=el|access-date=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March two villages in Western Macedonia, [[Damaskinia]] and [[Dragasia]], were quarantined after several cases among their residents were confirmed. Movement in and out of the villages was banned, allowing only medical staff and municipal staff to supply medication and food.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/ellada/94293_koronoios-se-karantina-ta-horia-damaskinia-kai-dragasia|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a3\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c7\u03c9\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac \u0394\u03b1\u03bc\u03b1\u03c3\u03ba\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ac \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac|last=|first=|date=2020-03-16|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2|language=el|trans-title=Coronavirus: The villages of Damaskinia and Dragasia are quarantined|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref> On 18 March, Greece announced new coronavirus restrictions pertaining to migrant camps. For thirty days, the movement of camp residents would be restricted to small groups between 7am and 7pm, which could only include one person per family and would be controlled by police on public transport. Specialised medical teams were sent to the camps for the creation of virus isolation areas and compulsory temperature checking. All other visits to the camps whether by individuals or organisations were suspended for at least 14 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/greece-unveils-new-coronavirus-restrictions-in-migrant-camps-12553024|title=Greece unveils new coronavirus restrictions in migrant camps|date=March 18, 2020|agency=Channel New Asia}}</ref> On the same day, Deputy Minister of Civil Protection and Crisis Management Nikos Hardalias announced a ban on public gatherings of 10 or more people and the imposition of a 1,000 euro fine on violators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/koinonia/koronoios-se-ischy-i-apagoreysi-synathroiseon-ano-ton-10-atomon-oi-apodektes-metakiniseis.7605395.html|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a3\u03b5 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c7\u03cd \u03b7 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1\u03b8\u03c1\u03bf\u03af\u03c3\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u03ac\u03bd\u03c9 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd 10 \u03b1\u03c4\u03cc\u03bc\u03c9\u03bd - \u039f\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03b4\u03b5\u03ba\u03c4\u03ad\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03b9\u03bd\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2|last=|first=|date=|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|trans-title=Coronavirus: Ban on public gatherings of 10 or more people - Acceptable movements|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-idUSKBN2152YH|title=Greece bans gatherings of 10 people and more, effective Thursday|date=2020-03-19|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, [[Ministry of Maritime Affairs and Insular Policy (Greece)|Minister of Maritime Affairs and Insular Policy]] Giannis Plakiotakis announced that only permanent residents and supply trucks would be allowed to travel to the Greek islands, with effect from 6am local time on 21 March. Travellers need to provide proof of permanent residence (via a tax certificate) on the island to which they wish to travel. People who are already on the islands and wish to leave are allowed to return to the mainland.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/oikonomia/94785_koronoios-ta-metra-gia-ergazomenoys-ki-epiheiriseis|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03cc\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b9 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2|language=el|trans-title=Coronavirus: Measures for Workers and Businesses|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250865/article/ekathimerini/news/government-bans-travel-to-the-islands-for-non-residents|title=Government bans travel to the islands for non-residents {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the Greek government announced a ban on all nonessential transport and movement across the country, starting from 6 a.m on 23 March until 6 April. Movement is permitted only for a prescribed set of reasons that include moving to or from the workplace during normal business hours, shopping for food or medicine, visiting a doctor or assisting a person in need of help, exercising individually or in pairs or walking a pet, attending a ceremony (wedding, baptism, funeral etc.), and cases of divorced parents moving to ensure communication with their children. People returning to their permanent places of residence will also be exempt. Citizens leaving their home are required to carry their ID or passport with them, as well as some type of certification explaining the reason for their movement which has to be confirmed by their employer or by themselves. The options include filling in a special form that can be downloaded from the government website forma.gov.gr, sending a free SMS to the number 13033, or explaining their reason in a signed handwritten declaration. The information needed include the name, home address, time of departure from home, and the specific reason for transport that falls under one of the exceptions. Members of the government and parliament as well as all Health, Civil Protection, Law Enforcement and Armed Forces personnel were excluded from the measure. The [[Hellenic Police]], the [[Municipal Police (Greece)|Municipal Police]], the [[Hellenic Coast Guard]] and the National Transparency Authority are required to enforce the restrictions and issue fines of 150 euros for each offense.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iefimerida.gr/ellada/apagoreysi-kykloforias-pos-tha-pate-deytera-doyleia|title=\u0391\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2: \u03a0\u03ce\u03c2 \u03b8\u03b1 \u03c0\u03ac\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0394\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03b4\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03ac -\u03a0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c4\u03c1\u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 {{!}} \u0395\u039b\u039b\u0391\u0394\u0391|last=IEFIMERIDA.GR|first=NEWSROOM|date=2020-03-22|website=iefimerida.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forma.gov.gr/|title=Instructions to the public|last=|first=|date=|website=forma.gov.gr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.in.gr/2020/03/22/english-edition/greece-quarantine-mitsotakis-declares-nationwide-lockdown-6am-tomorrow/|title=Greece in quarantine: Mitsotakis declares nationwide lockdown as of 6am tomorrow|last=in.gr|date=2020-03-22|website=in.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250917/article/ekathimerini/news/pm-announces-full-lockdown-in-bid-to-curb-coronavirus-spread|title=PM announces full lockdown in bid to curb coronavirus spread {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On the same day, it was also announced that daytime public transport services will be limited, although ensuring sufficient service during business hours. Journeys by car are only permitted for the specific exemptions, and the driver may only have one passenger in the vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.in.gr/2020/03/22/greece/apagoreysi-kykloforias-analytikos-odigos-pou-tha-epitrepetai-metakinisi-ti-tha-isxysei-gia-tous-ergazomenous/|title=\u0391\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2: \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b4\u03b7\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2 - \u03a0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b8\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c4\u03c1\u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 -\u03a4\u03b9 \u03b8\u03b1 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c7\u03cd\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03bf\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2|last=in.gr|date=2020-03-22|website=in.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, Deputy Minister for Civil Protection and Crisis Management Nikos Hardalias announced additional restrictive measures for a duration of 14 days in the [[Municipalities and communities of Greece|municipalities]] of [[Kastoria]], [[Orestida]] and [[Nestorio]] of [[Kastoria (regional unit)|Kastoria Regional Unit]] as well as those of [[Xanthi]] and [[Myki, Greece|Myki]] of [[Xanthi (regional unit)|Xanthi Regional Unit]]. A night curfew was imposed from 8:00 p.m. until 8:00 a.m. the following morning and some options of the lockdown movement permits were suspended. Only close relatives can attend a funeral and pet owners are allowed to walk their pet for up to 15 minutes and near their house only.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.civilprotection.gr/el/simantika-themata/prostheta-perioristika-metra-gia-ti-metakinisi-ton-politon-stoys-dimoys-xanthis|title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c3\u03b8\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03ce\u03bd \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u039e\u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03b7\u03c2, \u039c\u03cd\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2, \u039a\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03c2, \u039f\u03c1\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u039d\u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03c9 \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03bf\u03cd COVID-19|last=generalsecretary|date=2020-03-31|website=\u0393\u03b5\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0393\u03c1\u03b1\u03bc\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|language=el|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==== Travel restrictions abroad ====\nOn 9 March, the [[Hellenic Civil Aviation Authority]] announced the temporary suspension of all flights to and from [[northern Italy]], affecting all Greek airports and all airlines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250404/article/ekathimerini/news/all-flights-to-and-from-northern-italy-suspended|title=All flights to and from northern Italy suspended {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On 14 March the suspension was extended to all passenger flights to and from Italy, excluding cargo and sanitary ones.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-death/greece-reports-two-more-coronavirus-fatalities-suspends-all-flights-to-italy-idUSKBN2110H1|title=Greece reports two more coronavirus fatalities, bans all flights to Italy|date=March 14, 2020|agency=Reuters}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March Greece closed its borders with [[Albania]] and [[North Macedonia]], deciding to suspend all road, sea and air links with these countries, while only permitting the transportation of goods and the entry of Greek nationals and residents. The suspension of ferry services to and from [[Italy]], air links to [[Spain]], as well as the prohibition of all cruise ships and sailboats docking in Greek ports was also decided.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/politiki/koronoios-ektakta-metra-kleinoyn-ta-synora-me-alvania-kai-v-makedonia-tilefonima-mitsotaki-se-ieronymo.7602425.html|title=\u0395\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 - \u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0392. \u039c\u03b1\u03ba\u03b5\u03b4\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 - \u03a0\u03b1\u03c1\u03ad\u03bc\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b5\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> The same day it was announced that a 14-day home restriction will be mandatory for those who enter the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/koinonia/koronoios-kleinoyn-ta-emporika-katastimata-se-karantina-osoi-erchontai-apo-exoteriko.7603146.html|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 - \u03a3\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u03b9 \u03ad\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03b5\u03be\u03c9\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, Greece and the other EU member states decided to close their external borders to all non-EU nationals. In Greece, the entry of citizens of countries from outside the European Union is only permitted for a condition that relates exclusively to an emergency or family matter. All private pleasure boats from abroad were also banned from entering the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iefimerida.gr/kosmos/koronoios-i-ee-kleinei-ta-synora-karantina-ellada|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0397 \u0395\u0395 \u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 -\u03a0\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03b8\u03b1 \u03bc\u03c0\u03b1\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c3\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 {{!}} \u039a\u039f\u03a3\u039c\u039f\u03a3|last=IEFIMERIDA.GR|first=NEWSROOM|date=2020-03-18|website=iefimerida.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On 19 March, Turkey closed the land border crossings with Greece at [[Karaa\u011fa\u00e7, Edirne|Karaa\u011fa\u00e7]] and [[\u0130psala|Ipsala]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/kosmos/94854_koronoios-i-toyrkia-kleinei-ta-synora-me-tin-ellada-kai-ti-boylgaria|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0397 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7 \u0392\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03b1|date=2020-03-18|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2|language=el|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nFrom 23 March, Greece suspended all passenger flights from the UK as well as all sea, rail and road connections with Turkey, with an exception for Greek citizens and those who have residence permits or whose main residence is in Greece, as well as trucks and ships that transport goods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.gr/news/ellada/story/212372/koronoios-telos-apo-ta-mesanyxta-oi-ptiseis-apo-vretania-kai-toyrkia|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03c0\u03c4\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u0392\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03a4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03af\u03b1|last=Newsroom|date=2020-03-23|website=CNN.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic measures ===\nOn 18 March, in a joint news conference, [[Ministry of Finance (Greece)|Finance Minister]] [[Christos Staikouras]], Labour Minister [[Giannis Vroutsis|Yannis Vroutsis]], and Development & Investments Minister [[Adonis Georgiadis]] announced a package of measures to support the economy, businesses and employees. The measures include the suspension, for four months, of tax and social security obligations of corporations that were ordered to close by the state decree, with the sole condition that they do not dismiss any workers. This measure covers about 220,000 businesses and 600,000 employees. The measures also include an \u20ac800 stipend as well as a four-month suspension of payment of March taxes on employees of businesses the activity of which was suspended and on freelance professionals who work in sectors affected by the pandemic. The reduction of VAT tax from 24% to 6% on pharmaceutical products such as gloves, masks and antiseptics was also announced. Moreover, the Finance Minister  announced the inclusion of Greece in an emergency assets purchases\u2019 program worth 750 billion euros launched by the [[European Central Bank]], and also stated the 3.5% primary surplus target for Greece is no longer in effect, according to a [[Eurogroup]] decision.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tanea.gr/2020/03/18/english-edition/greece-takes-sweeping-measures-to-protect-business-labour-from-coronavirus-tempest/|title=Greece takes sweeping measures to protect business, labour from coronavirus tempest|last=Team|first=TANEA|date=2020-03-18|website=\u03a4\u0391 \u039d\u0395\u0391|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250809/article/ekathimerini/business/greece-says-ecb-emergency-package-makes-12-billion-euro-in-debt-eligible|title=Greece says ECB emergency package makes 12 billion euro in debt eligible {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]] [[Kyriakos Mitsotakis]], in a nationally televised address, announced the revision of the [[Government budget|State Budget]] to allocate more than 10 billion euros in support of the economy. The suspension of tax and social security obligations of corporations and the number of beneficiaries of the \u20ac800 stipend was extended to include all businesses harmed by the pandemic, all freelancers and self-employed workers and the majority of private sector workers. The state will also cover the cost of beneficiaries\u2019 insurance, pension, and health payments. The PM also stated that the Easter bonus would be paid in full to all employees and announced a special bonus for health and civil protection workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsbomb.gr/politikh/story/1064307/koronoios-mitsotakis-to-doro-pasxa-tha-katavlithei-kanonika-aytoi-tha-lavoyn-800-eyro|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 - \"\u03a4\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c3\u03af\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03bf\" \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7: \u0391\u03bd \u03c7\u03c1\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03af \u03b8\u03b1 \u03c0\u03ac\u03c1\u03c9 \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03cd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2|last=Newsroom|date=|website=Newsbomb|language=el|trans-title=Coronavirus - Mitsotakis: If needed I'll take new restriction measures|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250836/article/ekathimerini/news/greek-pm-announces-more-financial-aid-bonus-for-health-workers|title=Greek PM announces more financial aid, bonus for health workers {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspension of businesses and workplaces ===\nOn 12 March, a two-week closure of all theatres, courthouses, cinemas, gyms, playgrounds and clubs was announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tanea.gr/2020/03/12/greece/ektakta-metra-kleinoun-kinimatografoi-theatra-kai-kentra-diaskedasis/|title=\u0395\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03ba\u03b9\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03c6\u03bf\u03b9, \u03b8\u03ad\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03ba\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03ba\u03ad\u03b4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2|date=12 March 2020|website=tanea.gr|language=el|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March, the nationwide closure of all shopping centres, cafes, restaurants, bars, museums and archaeological sites and food outlets, excluding supermarkets, pharmacies and food outlets that offer take-away and delivery only, was announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250618/article/ekathimerini/news/malls-cafes-bars-eateries-to-close-as-coronavirus-cases-rise-to-190|title=Malls, cafes, bars, eateries to close as coronavirus cases rise to 190|date=13 March 2020|website=ekathimerini.com|language=en|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On 14 March, all organised beaches and ski resorts were closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnos.gr/politiki/93995_koronoios-kleinoyn-paralies-kai-hionodromika-me-entoli-mitsotaki|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bb\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c7\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03bc\u03b5 \u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u039c\u03b7\u03c4\u03c3\u03bf\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7|date=2020-03-14|website=\u0388\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2|language=el|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the government announced the closure of all hotels across the country, from midnight on March 22 and until the end of April. Only hotels that accommodate personnel that guard the border will continue to operate, as well as three hotels in Athens and Thessaloniki and one hotel per [[Regional units of Greece|regional unit]] will remain open. Moreover, all Greek citizens returning from abroad will be subjected to mandatory surveillance and isolation for at least 14 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.gr/news/ellada/story/211904/koronoios-kleinoyn-kai-ta-xenodoxeia|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03be\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03b4\u03bf\u03c7\u03b5\u03af\u03b1|last=Newsroom|date=2020-03-19|website=CNN.gr|language=el|trans-title=Coronavirus: Hotels are also closed|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://int.ert.gr/hotels-are-closing-greeks-returning-from-abroad-will-be-put-under-quarantine/|title=Hotels are closing- Greeks returning from abroad will be put under quarantine|last=Tsirigotaki|first=Eve|date=2020-03-19|website=ERT International|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref> On 22 March, all parks, recreation areas and marinas were also closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.in.gr/2020/03/22/greece/apagoreysi-kykloforias-analytikos-odigos-pou-tha-epitrepetai-metakinisi-ti-tha-isxysei-gia-tous-ergazomenous/|title=\u0391\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03ba\u03c5\u03ba\u03bb\u03bf\u03c6\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2: \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03bb\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b4\u03b7\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2 - \u03a0\u03bf\u03cd \u03b8\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c4\u03c1\u03ad\u03c0\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7 -\u03a4\u03b9 \u03b8\u03b1 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c7\u03cd\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b5\u03c1\u03b3\u03b1\u03b6\u03bf\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2|last=in.gr|date=2020-03-22|website=in.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n=== Closure of educational institutions ===\nStarting on 28 February, with four confirmed cases in the country, the precautionary local closure of schools was decided when there was concern that members of these school communities may have come into contact with a coronavirus carrier. On the same day, all educational trips abroad programmed by Greek schools were suspended and various municipalities around the country began disinfecting schools locally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ert.gr/eidiseis/ellada/kinonia/koronoios-ichnilateitai-i-poreia-ton-nosoynton-metra-profylaxis-anastellontai-ta-episkeptiria/|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u0399\u03c7\u03bd\u03b7\u03bb\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03af\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03bd\u03bf\u03c3\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd-\u039c\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c6\u03cd\u03bb\u03b1\u03be\u03b7\u03c2-\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b1 \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c0\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 (video)|last=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03ca\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5|first=\u0397-\u0392|date=2020-02-28|website=ert.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ieidiseis.gr/ellada/item/36949-koronoios-pote-tha-apofasistoyn-ta-kleista-sxoleia-stin-ellada|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2: \u03a0\u03cc\u03c4\u03b5 \u03b8\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c6\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac \u03c3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1|last=iEidiseis|website=www.ieidiseis.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ieidiseis.gr/ellada/item/36906-koronoios-stin-ellada-proliptikes-apolymanseis-se-dimosia-ktiria-apo-ton-dimo-iliou|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03c0\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03ac\u03bd\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03ba\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0394\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf \u0399\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5|last=iEidiseis|website=www.ieidiseis.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> On 4 March, the closure of all public and private educational institutions of all levels in [[Elis (regional unit)|Ilia]], [[Achaea]] and [[Zakynthos]] was decided<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ieidiseis.gr/ellada/item/37222-koronoios-stin-ellada-ektakta-metra-anakoinonei-i-kyvernisi|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1: \u03a4\u03b1 \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 \u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1|last=iEidiseis|website=www.ieidiseis.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> and from 8 March all educational trips within the country were suspended.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn 10 March, the operation of all schools, universities, daycare centres and all other educational establishments was suspended nationwide for fourteen days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kathimerini.gr/1068505/article/epikairothta/ellada/kleinoyn-gia-dyo-evdomades-sxoleia-panepisthmia-paidikoi-sta8moi-kai-frontisthria|title=\u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03bd \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b4\u03cd\u03bf \u03b5\u03b2\u03b4\u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1, \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b9\u03b1, \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b8\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1 {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.kathimerini.gr|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> A special purpose leave of 15 days was introduced for working parents.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news247.gr/politiki/koronoios-ektakta-metra-adeia-eidikoy-skopoy-stoys-goneis.7599804.html|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 - \u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03c4\u03b1 \u03bc\u03ad\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1: \u0386\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 \u03b5\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03c0\u03bf\u03cd \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03b3\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03af\u03c2|website=www.news247.gr|language=el|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Ten days later, on 20 March, the closure period was extended such that all educational institutions would remain closed until 10 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alfavita.gr/ekpaideysi/316080_kleista-eos-tis-10-aprilioy-sholeia-kai-panepistimia|title=\u039a\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac \u03ad\u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b9\u03c2 10 \u0391\u03c0\u03c1\u03b9\u03bb\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b9\u03b1|website=Alfavita|language=el|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n=== Suspension of religious practices ===\n\nIn the initial stages of the coronavirus outbreak, the [[Church of Greece]] had announced that the [[Eucharist#Eastern Orthodoxy|Holy Communion]], with the appearance of bread and wine, would continue as a practice.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\">{{cite web | last=Editorial | first=Reuters | title=In era of coronavirus, Greek church says Holy Communion will carry on | website=U.S. | date=9 March 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-greece-church-idUSKBN20W2N1 | access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref> Initially, the [[Holy Synod#The Greek Holy Synod|Holy Synod]] had defended the practice of the Holy Communion, with Metropolitan Seraphim saying that the Holy Communion was without blemish because it represents the blood and body of Christ.<ref name=\"Reuters 9 March\"/><ref name=VOA>{{cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/science-health/coronavirus-outbreak/coronavirus-sparks-church-state-controversy-greece|title=Coronavirus Sparks Church-State Controversy in Greece |author=Anthee Carasava|agency=Voice of America|date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Church's stance prompted criticism from the opposition [[Syriza]] party, with former [[Prime Minister|prime minister]] [[Alexis Tsipras]] criticising the church stance, as did former health minister [[Pavlos Polakis]].<ref name=Straights>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/world/europe/coronavirus-bug-sparks-holy-communion-row-in-greece|title=Coronavirus: Bug sparks Holy Communion row in Greece|agency=Straights Times|date=9 March 2020}}</ref> In a statement in early March 2020, the governing Holy Synod of the Orthodox Church of Greece advised sick worshippers to temporarily avoid crowds and close contact with others.<ref name=Straights/>\n\nSome high-profile Greek medical doctors publicly supported the continuation of practicing Holy Communion, drawing criticism from the Greek Association of Hospital Doctors.<ref name=\"Brzozowski Michalopoulos 2020\">{{cite web | last=Brzozowski | first=Alexandra | last2=Michalopoulos | first2=Sarantis | title=Catholics take measures against coronavirus while Greek Orthodox Church 'prays' | website=www.euractiv.com | date=9 March 2020 | url=https://www.euractiv.com/section/health-consumers/news/catholics-take-measures-against-coronavirus-while-greek-orthodox-church-prays/ | access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> ({{lang-el|\u039f\u03bc\u03bf\u03c3\u03c0\u03bf\u03bd\u03b4\u03af\u03b1 \u0395\u03bd\u03ce\u03c3\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u039d\u03bf\u03c3\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u0393\u03b9\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03ce\u03bd \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2}} (OENGE)).\n\nOn 11 March, the [[Prime Minister of Greece]] [[Kyriakos Mitsotakis]], in a nationally televised address, told the public to follow the instructions of doctors and experts, and the Church of Greece to cooperate in enforcing the public health regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tovima.gr/2020/03/11/international/mitsotakis-calls-for-unity-personal-responsibility-cooperation-of-archbishop-to-limit-covid-19/|title=Mitsotakis calls for unity, personal responsibility, cooperation of Archbishop to limit COVID-19|last=Team|first=\u03a4\u03bf\u0392\u0397\u039c\u0391|date=11 March 2020|website=\u0395\u03b9\u03b4\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 - \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 - \u03a4\u03bf \u0392\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1 Online|language=el|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Two days later, the [[Archbishopric of Athens|Archbishop of Athens and all Greece]] [[Ieronymos II of Athens|Ieronymos]] stated that the Church agreed with and would implement the public health precautionary measures taken by the national authorities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tovima.gr/2020/03/13/society/koronoios-ieronymos-i-ekklisia-mas-oudepote-stathike-apenanti-stin-epistimi-i-epixeirise-na-tin-ypokatastisei/|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03cc\u03c2 - \u0399\u03b5\u03c1\u03ce\u03bd\u03c5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2: \u0397 \u0395\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03af\u03b1 \u03bc\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03ad\u03c0\u03bf\u03c4\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03b8\u03b7\u03ba\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03ad\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b7 \u03ae \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c7\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bd\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9|last=Team|first=\u03a4\u03bf\u0392\u0397\u039c\u0391|date=13 March 2020|website=\u0395\u03b9\u03b4\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 - \u03bd\u03ad\u03b1 - \u03a4\u03bf \u0392\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1 Online|language=el|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, after having been briefed by infectious disease spokesman Sotiris Tsiodras, the Greek Orthodox Church announced the suspension of all daily liturgies and sacraments; churches were to remain open only for private prayer, weddings and baptisms were indefinitely suspended and funerals were to be held with only the immediate family present. The Greek Orthodox Church announced that Sunday liturgies were to take place from March 22 to April 11, but to be restricted to the [[Eucharist]] sacraments, performed between 7 and 8 in the morning.<ref name=\"kath\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250716/article/ekathimerini/news/greek-orthodox-church-agrees-to-suspend-daily-services-sacraments-over-coronavirus|title=Greek Orthodox Church agrees to suspend daily services, sacraments over coronavirus|agency=Ekatherimini|date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Following the announcement of the Greek Orthodox Church,<ref name=\"kath2\" /> the Greek Prime Minister announced the government's decision to suspend services in all areas of religious worship of any religion or dogma from 16\u201330 March,<ref name=\"kathimerini\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kathimerini.gr/1069449/article/epikairothta/politikh/anastellontai-oles-oi-8rhskeytikes-leitoyrgies-me-apofash-ths-kyvernhshs|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bf\u03b9 \u03b8\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03ba\u03b5\u03c5\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ad\u03c2 \u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03af\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c6\u03b1\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03c5\u03b2\u03ad\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2 {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.kathimerini.gr|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref> effectively suspending the Greek Orthodox Sunday [[Divine Liturgy|Divine Liturgies]] for that period too.<ref name=\"kath2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/250756/article/ekathimerini/news/greek-church-finally-toes-state-line-on-coronavirus|title=Greek Church finally toes state line on coronavirus {{!}} Kathimerini|website=www.ekathimerini.com|language=English|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n== Refugees and migrants ==\nOn February 27, prime minister Mitsotakis announced that illegal entry into Greece would no longer tolerated; as this would be a threat to public health.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Karaoulanis |first1=Theodore |last2=\u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03ac\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 |first2=\u0398\u03bf\u03b4\u03c9\u03c1\u03ae\u03c2 |title=\u0391\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c3\u03b5 \u03cc\u03c3\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c3\u03c6\u03c5\u03b3\u03b5\u03c2 - \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03ad\u03c1\u03c7\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b1\u03c0\u03cc \u0399\u03c1\u03ac\u03bd, \u0391\u03c6\u03b3\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03bd \u03c0\u03c1\u03bf\u03b1\u03bd\u03ae\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5 \u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03c9\u03b8\u03c5\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2, \u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03c9 \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03bf\u03cd |url=https://www.euractiv.gr/section/koinoniki-eyropi/news/anaschesi-sta-synora-se-osoys-prosfyges-metanastes-proerchontai-apo-iran-afganistan-proaniggeile-o-prothypoyrgos-logo-koronoioy/ |website=www.euractiv.gr |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=el |date=27 February 2020}}</ref> According to various estimates about 150,600 [[displaced person]]s are located in Greece.<ref name=\"Prothero\">{{cite news |last1=Prothero |first1=Mitch |title=In Greece, the government prepares for a crisis that is beyond its capacity to handle |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-greece-prepares-for-crisis-2020-3 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=2020 |ref=Prothero}}</ref> In the existing camps, doctors, NGOs and refugees considered that measures against the spread of the coronavirus are lacking as people live in overcrowded spaces with little access to proper health services.<ref name=\"AlJazeera\"/><ref name=\"Prothero\"/><ref name=\"Campana\">{{cite news |last1=Campana |first1=Fahrinisa |last2=Patrick |first2=Strickland |title=The Looming Refugee Coronavirus Disaster |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/refugees-coronavirus-greece.html |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Slate |date=2020 |ref=Campana}}</ref> On March 24, 21 international human rights organizations active in Greece including [[Amnesty International]], the [[Human Rights Watch]] and [[ActionAid]] published an open call to the Greek government to take immediate measures to prevent the spread of COVID-19 in the Reception and Identification Centres, where refugees live. The conditions of the centres were criticised as deplorable and dangerous to both the refugees and public health.<ref name=\"HRW\">{{cite web |title=Greece: Move Asylum Seekers, Migrants to Safety |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/24/greece-move-asylum-seekers-migrants-safety |website=HRW |accessdate=27 March 2020 |ref=HRW}}</ref> [[M\u00e9decins Sans Fronti\u00e8res]] which has a clinic near the Moria camp declared that the numbers in the camps had reached levels such that they could not handle an outbreak of infection within the camp. The government further announced that movement of refugees outside the camps would be restricted as facilities are prepared for confirmed cases,<ref name=\"Fotiadis\">{{cite news |last1=Fotiadis |first1=Apostolos |title=Greece Ramps up Restrictions but Faces Criticism over Coronavirus Response |url=https://balkaninsight.com/2020/03/25/greece-ramps-up-restrictions-but-faces-criticism-over-coronavirus-response/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |publisher=Balkan Insight |date=2020 |ref=Fotiadis}}</ref> and that it would only allow small goups of refugees and migrants to temporarily exit the camps to obtain basic supplies.<ref name=\"AlJazeera\">{{cite news |title=Greece curbs refugee movement in camps over coronavirus fears |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/greece-curbs-refugee-movement-camps-coronavirus-fears-200318162208279.html |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=2020 |ref=AlJazeera}}</ref> For the coronavirus fear, in the island of Chios some immigrants pretend that they are new arrivals so that they are transferred to Greek mainland.<ref>[https://www.ethnos.gr/ellada/96330_hios-metanastes-paristanoyn-toys-neoafihthentes-gia-na-fygoyn-logo-koronoioy \"Chios: Immigrants pretend the new arrivals ...\", Ethnos.gr, March 26, 2020]</ref> \n\nOn March 28, the Turkish interior minister announced that 5,800 refugees and migrants that had unsuccessfully attempted to cross the Greek-Turkish border had been relocated to Turkish cities due to the coronavirus pandemic. He also announced that as soon as the pandemic subsided those populations would be returned to the border.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u03a4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c1\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a5\u03a0\u0395\u03a3: \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03b7 \u03bb\u03ae\u03be\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03bf\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03ca\u03bf\u03cd \u03c0\u03c1\u03cc\u03c3\u03c6\u03c5\u03b3\u03b5\u03c2 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac\u03c3\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u03be\u03b1\u03bd\u03ac \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03cd\u03bd\u03bf\u03c1\u03b1 |url=https://www.sofokleousin.gr/tourkos-ypes-meta-ti-liksi-tou-koronoiou-prosfyges-metanastes-ksa |website=www.sofokleousin.gr |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=el}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, it was reported that an African couple were infected in the [[Vathy, Euboea#Ritsona|Ritsona]] refugee camp in Central Greece, the wife having given birth.<ref>[https://www.ethnos.gr/ellada/97339_thetiko-ston-koronoio-zeygari-apo-tin-afriki-sto-hot-pot-tis-ritsonas \"Positive to coronavirus, a couple from Africa ...\", Ethnos, 31-3-2020]</ref><ref>[https://www.skai.gr/news/ygeia/poedin-thetiki-ston-koronoio-metanastria-apo-ti-ritsona-pou-gennise-sto-aleksandra \"Positive to coronavirus, a Ritsona woman immigrant who gave birth in Alexandra Hospital\", Skai.gr, 31-3-2020]</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]\n* [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n* [[Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in November 2019 \u2013 January 2020]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://eody.gov.gr/ - Official website of the Greek [[National Public Health Organization (Greece)|National Public Health Organization]] with information regarding the progress of the pandemic in the country\n* [https://lab.imedd.org/covid19/ COVID\u201419] \u2013 map with various updated statistics\n* [http://geochoros.survey.ntua.gr/coronavirus/ CoVID-GEO] - geographical analysis and mapping of Coronavirus COVID-19 related world data through a web-based platform developed by the GeoCHOROS Geospatial Analysis and Research Group at the National Technical University of Athens, Greece\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Greece]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Greece]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 in Greece]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Greece]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Dr.K.", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRefugees and migrants:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Greece"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Texas, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas\n| map1 = Map_of_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Texas_latest.svg\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1 =\n{{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location = [[Texas]], U.S\n| first_case = [[San Antonio]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date = January 2020\n| confirmed_cases= 3,346<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in Texas (Dashboard) |url=https://txdshs.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/ed483ecd702b4298ab01e8b9cafc8b83 |website=Texas Department of State Health Services |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases = 131\n| deaths = 46\n<!--As of March 30, 2020-->\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached the U.S. state of [[Texas]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Texas medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Panic buying in Texas in response to the coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|upright|Empty shelves from [[panic buying]] at the [[Sams Club]] in [[Lufkin, Texas]], on March 13, 2020.]]\n'''March 4:''' public health officials in [[Fort Bend County, Texas|Fort Bend County]] reported a presumptive positive test result in a man in his 70s who had recently traveled outside the United States. The man was hospitalized in stable condition. The new case was the first in Texas outside of US nationals evacuated from Hubei Province and the ''Diamond Princess'' cruise ship to Joint Base San Antonio in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=Presumptive positive case of COVID-19 found in Fort Bend County, officials say|work=[[KTRK-TV]]|url=https://abc13.com/health/presumptive-case-of-covid-19-found-in-fort-bend-co/5977165/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=First case of 'presumptive positive' coronavirus confirmed in Fort Bend County|last1=Kamath|first1=Tulsi|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]|url=https://www.click2houston.com/news/local/2020/03/04/reports-first-case-of-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-fort-bend-county/}}</ref>\n'''March 5:''' Public health officials in Houston reported two confirmed cases in a man and a woman from northwest [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]]. Both cases are related to recent travel to Egypt.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Man, woman confirmed to be first cases of coronavirus in Harris County|last=Kamath|first=Tulsi|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]}}</ref> In the evening, an additional two cases, a man and a woman, were reported from Harris County also from the same travel group to Egypt. The woman is a staff member at [[Rice University]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=2 new presumptive positive coronavirus cases confirmed in Houston area, bringing total to 5; all cases connected to group who traveled to Egypt|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/}}</ref>\n'''March 6:''' Three new cases were reported, one in [[Houston]] and two in Fort Bend County. All cases were part of a group that had traveled together to Egypt. This brought the Texas cases to 8, all in the Houston region.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/harris-county-coronavirus-total-outbreak-fort-bend-15111223.php|title=More coronavirus cases reported in Houston area|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbchealth.org/fort-bend-county-health-human-services-reports-2-additional-presumptive-positive-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-overall-total-to-3/|title=Fort Bend County Health & Human Services reports 2 additional presumptive positive cases of COVID-19, bringing overall total to 3|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> On March 9, [[Collin County]] reported 3 new presumptive cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |title=Parents, 3-year-old child test positive for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-10 |website=WFAA |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011925/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The patients were a married couple and their 3-year-old child who attended [[Frisco Independent School District|Frisco ISD]]. The man tested positive for the virus after visiting [[Silicon Valley]] in late February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |title=Frisco man tests 'presumptive positive' for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-09 |website=WFAA |language=en-US |url-status=live |access-date=2020-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202824/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |archive-date=2020-03-10 }}</ref>\n\n'''March 10:''' [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] and [[Tarrant County, Texas|Tarrant County]] both announced one presumptive case in each county, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |title=First 'presumptive positive' cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Dallas, Tarrant counties |last=[[WFAA]] |website=WFAA |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011318/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On March 11, [[Houston]] mayor [[Sylvester Turner]] announced cancellation of the [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] after declaring the outbreak as a public health emergency.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Platoff |first1=Emma |title=Houston Rodeo called off as fears about new coronavirus continue to spread in Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311191252/https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first possible case of community spread was announced the same day, in a patient who had not traveled out of the state.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ackerman |first1=Todd |last2=Hensley |first2=Nicole |title='The tip of the iceberg': Coronavirus 'community spread' has started in Houston area |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Montgomery-County-patient-is-first-Houston-area-15123593.php |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lakewood Church]] in Houston, one of the nation's biggest mega-churches announced it was canceling in-person services till further notice.<ref>[https://www.khou.com/mobile/article/news/latest-coronavirus-updates-houston-texas-march-10-2020/285-1700bfab-1e04-4de4-a02f-ad4cb38e6ac3 Latest coronavirus updates: Lakewood Church suspends in-person services], KHOU (CBS affiliate), updated March 12, 2020.</ref> On March 12, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] announced five additional positive cases with one of the cases being the first instance of community spread in the [[North Texas]] area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ura |first1=Alexa |title=Dallas County officials say community spread of coronavirus has occurred in North Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/covid-19-community-spread-arrives-dallas-county/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> A day later, the cities of [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[San Antonio]], and [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], as well as [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]] and [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]] counties, announced confirmed cases. San Antonio also announced a ban of gatherings of 500 or more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tamplin |first1=Harley |title=What we know about the 44 coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/what-we-know-about-the-36-coronavirus-patients-in-texas/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |website=[[KXAN]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n'''March 13:''' [[University of Texas]] president [[Gregory L. Fenves]] announced that his wife Carmel had contracted Coronavirus after a trip to New York City. In an open letter to UT staff, faculty, and students, Fenves stated his wife began exhibiting flu-like symptoms after their trip, during which they attended several events with alumni and students, and was tested positive for COVID-19. Both Fenves, his wife, and an additional family member are in self-isolation, and the president has advised community members to follow CDC [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic#Prevention|preventive measures]] against the spread of the virus.<ref>Drew Knight [https://www.kvue.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/ut-austin-presidents-wife-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/269-13f8b439-61b2-4233-b426-69982ecf3aa7 University of Texas president's wife tests positive for coronavirus; UT President Gregory L. Fenves made the announcement in a letter to students on Friday.] March 13, 2020</ref> A presumptive case was reported and confirmed in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]]. The man is in his 40s and is in self-quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/news/2020/03/13/first-positive-case-coronavirus-covid-19-reported-el-paso/5048557002/|title=First presumptive positive case of coronavirus reported in El Paso area|date=March 13, 2020|work=El Paso Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n'''March 16:''' Matagorda County officials announced the second positive case of COVID-19 in Matagorda County. The patient, a man in his late 90s, died Sunday evening at Matagorda Regional Medical Center with symptoms consistent with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite new |title=What we know about the 30 Houston Area coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://abc13.com/health/what-we-know-about-the-30-houston-area-coronavirus-cases/5999764/|accessdate=16 March 2020 |website=[[KTRK-TV|ABC13]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second death in Texas has been reported on March 17, of a resident of a retirement community in Arlington who died on Sunday, March 15.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/arlington-resident-dies-from-coronavirus-first-in-north-texas/2333046/ Arlington Resident Dies From Coronavirus, First in North Texas \u2013 NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]</ref>\n\n'''March 17:''' The third death in Texas has been reported on March 18, of a resident in Plano who died in a local hospital on March 17.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/plano-man-infected-with-covid-19-dies-in-local-hospital/2333587/ Plano Man Infected With COVID-19 Dies in Local Hospital]</ref>\n\n[[Bell County, Texas]] announced its first death, a woman, on March 26.<ref>[https://www.fox44news.com/news/breaking-news/breaking-first-covid-19-death-reported-in-central-texas/#/questions/2574674 BREAKING: First COVID-19 death reported in Central Texas] Fox 44 News, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|300px|Texas is one of several states that have delegated [[stay-at-home order]] decisions to the county and municipal level.]]\n\nOn March 2, San Antonio Mayor [[Ron Nirenberg]] and [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]] both declared a \"local state of disaster and a public health emergency\" after an individual was mistakenly released from quarantine at Joint Base San Antonio by the CDC before a third test for coronavirus returned a positive result.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=Bexar County joins San Antonio in declaring public health emergency over coronavirus|last=Floyd|first=Jackson|url=https://www.kens5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bexar-county-coronavirus-public-health-emergency/273-788a002b-1b08-49d0-9a27-da639e6fed47|work=[[KENS]]|url-status=live}}</ref> The city subsequently petitioned the US government to extend the quarantine of US nationals at Joint Base San Antonio; the petition was denied by Judge [[Xavier Rodriguez]] in the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Texas]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=3 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio loses court battle to extend coronavirus quarantine, Public Health Emergency declaration continues|last=Ruiz|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.ktsa.com/san-antonio-loses-court-battle-to-extend-coronavirus-quarantine-public-health-emergency-declaration-continues/|work=[[KTSA]]|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio, Bexar County in battle with the CDC over evacuees|last1=Caruba|first1=Lauren|last2=Christenson|first2=Sig|url=https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303160332/https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|archive-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Both the city of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] and [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] have declared a \"local disaster of public health emergency\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/public-health-emergency-declared-in-dallas-county/2329709/|title=Dallas Mayor Speaks After Health Emergency Declared: 'We Will Get Through This'|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Greg Abbott]] declared a statewide disaster for all [[List of counties in Texas|counties in the state]]. He also announced the first drive-through testing facility in San Antonio, and will expand to other cities across the state.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=13 March 2020|access-date=13 March 2020|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott issues disaster declaration over coronavirus|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/13/texas-coronavirus-cases-state-emergency-greg-abbott/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/texas/article/Dallas-bans-large-gatherings-amid-coronavirus-15128474.php|first=Paul J |last=Weber |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title= Texas declares disaster; UT president's wife tests positive |date=2020-03-13|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Lieutenant Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] said that although this disease could take your life, workers should get back to work.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=24 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020|title='Repulsive': Outrage as Texas Lieutenant Gov. Says Seniors Willing to Risk Coronavirus Infection to Protect Economy|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/24/repulsive-outrage-texas-lieutenant-gov-says-seniors-willing-risk-coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Governor Abbott directed health care professionals to postpone surgeries that are not \"medically necessary\", as well as suspend regulations to allow hospitals to have more than one patient in a room.<ref name=\"no shelter\">{{cite news |last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Gov. Greg Abbott resists calls for statewide shelter-in-place; moves to expand hospital capacity|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/22/texas-shelter-in-place-coronavirus-cases/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Controversially, Attorney General [[Ken Paxton]] later indicated that this included [[abortion]]s (except for the life or health of the mother).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |title=Texas and Ohio Include Abortion as Medical Procedures That Must Be Delayed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/coronavirus-texas-ohio-abortion.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Abbott also stated that there will not be any statewide [[shelter in place]] anytime soon, due to the fact that more than 200 counties do not have any cases.<ref name=\"no shelter\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fine|first1=Julie|title=No Shelter in Place Order for Texas, Gov. Abbott Says|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/no-shelter-in-place-order-for-texas-gov-abbott-says/2337034/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Abbott leaves the decision to the local government to set stricter guidelines. Two hours later, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] ordered residents of [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] to shelter in place beginning 11:59{{nbsp}}pm on the following day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Nic |last2=Keomoungkhoun |first2=Nataly |last3=Branham |first3=Dana |last4=Steele |first4=Tom |title=Dallas County residents ordered to stay home as new shelter-in-place rules are put in place |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/public-health/2020/03/22/dallas-county-residents-ordered-to-stay-home-as-new-shelter-in-place-rules-are-put-in-place/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Dallas Morning News |date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A day later on March 23, [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bell County officials issue shelter in place order|url=https://www.kwtx.com/content/news/Bell-County-officials-issue-shelter-in-place-order-569036731.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KWTX-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar]],<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\">{{cite news |last1=Samuels|first1=Alex|title=Local leaders to announce stay-at-home orders in Austin and San Antonio|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/23/austin-travis-county-issue-stay-home-order-tuesday/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Brazos County, Texas|Brazos]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazos County issues two-week shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.theeagle.com/news/brazos-county-issues-two-week-shelter-in-place/article_54221a48-6d50-11ea-a67b-db9bc130c196.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Eagle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron County issues shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.krgv.com/news/watch-cameron-county-officials-provide-update-on-covid-19|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KRGV.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Hunt County, Texas|Hunt]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jefferies|first1=Kevin|title=Hunt County Issues Shelter-In-Place Disaster Declaration|url=https://www.ketr.org/post/hunt-county-issues-shelter-place-disaster-declaration|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Kert Radio|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Waco, McLennan County issue shelter-in-place order; county cases rise to 20|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/news/government/waco-orders-shelter-in-place-commissioners-extend-order-to-county/article_e6225b23-6d3f-5ce1-b6d5-7486ee1bebae.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Waco Tribune-Herald|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Garner|first=Erica|title=Stephens County becomes first in Big Country to give 'Shelter in Place' order|url=https://www.bigcountryhomepage.com/health/coronavirus/stephens-county-becomes-first-in-big-country-to-give-shelter-in-place-order/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Big Country Homepage|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> counties and the city of [[Forney, Texas|Forney]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Richards|first=Mathew|title=City of Forney orders Shelter in Place until April 8|url=https://www.inforney.com/local-news/city-of-forney-to-consider-shelter-in-place-order-during/article_76f1a00e-6d2b-11ea-a99c-fbf23c0b7775.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=InForney.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> issued a shelter in place for their communities. [[Collin County, Texas|Collin]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guerrero|first1=Maria|title=Collin County Expected to Issue Shelter-In-Place on Tuesday|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Powell|first1=Nick|title=Galveston County plans to issue shelter-in-place order due to coronavirus|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Galveston-County-plans-to-issue-shelter-in-place-15152206.php|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Houston Chronicle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Harris County, Texas|Harris]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scherer |first1=Jasper |title=Here are all the businesses exempted from Harris County's stay-at-home order |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Here-are-all-the-businesses-exempted-from-Harris-15154736.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> [[Travis County, Texas|Travis]]<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\"/><ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\">{{cite news|title=Austin, Travis and Williamson Counties Issue Shelter-In-Place Order Effective Tuesday|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/tx/austin/news/2020/03/24/austin--travis-county-officials-to-issue-shelter-in-place-order-tuesday|accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Spectrum News|date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Williamson County, Texas|Williamson]]<ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\"/> counties issued same measures on March 24. However, Collin County had more relaxed guidelines for their shelter in place order. Collin County's order stated that all businesses are essential and would be allowed to remain open as long as they followed social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|title=Collin County Judge Issues 'Stay Home, Work Safe' Measures, Businesses to Remain Open|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Lt. Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] declared that \u2018lots of grandparents\u2019 would be willing to die to save the economy for their grandchildren.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/dan-patrick-seniors-are-willing-to-die-to-save-economy.html Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick: \u2018Lots of Grandparents\u2019 Willing to Die to Save Economy for Grandchildren] By Matt Stieb, Intelligencer, 23 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Sixth Street Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|[[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|Sixth Street]] in Austin after all bars and restaurants were ordered closed]]\nOn March 13, [[Six Flags]] (based in Texas) suspended operations to all their properties (12) nationwide as well in Mexico, that were operating in the month of March, until the end of the month; these include the two Texas parks, [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] and [[Six Flags Over Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2020/03/13/saying-they-are-re-evaluating-coronavirus-risks-six-flags-over-texas-closes-park/|title=Saying They Are Re-Evaluating Coronavirus Risks, Six Flags Over Texas Closes Park|website=KTVT|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> [[Sea World San Antonio]] announced plans to close from March 16 to April 1, along with all [[Schlitterbahn]] waterparks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pettaway |first1=Taylor |last2=Express-News |first2=mySA com / San Antonio |title=Six Flags Fiesta Texas, Schlitterbahn Resorts, SeaWorld closing for March amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Six-Flags-Fiesta-Texas-is-closing-for-the-15129177.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=San Antonio Express-News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, [[H-E-B]] announced that all their stores across the state, will reduce the hours, to help restock items. This also includes their pharmacies and [[Central Market (Texas)|Central Market]] locations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernandez |first1=Emily |title=H-E-B changes store hours to restock shelves amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200314/h-e-b-changes-store-hours-to-restock-shelves-amid-coronavirus-concerns |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Austin American-Statesman |date=March 14, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The announcement comes a day after, when the company announced that its Houston area stores would be the only locations to implement changes to their operations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schuetz |first1=R. A. |last2=Takahashi |first2=Paul |title=Houston-area grocers rush to restock as coronavirus-related demand spikes |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Grocers-rush-to-restock-as-coronavirus-related-15129078.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\nFor the first time in the event's history, [[South by Southwest]] was cancelled as a result of local health concerns about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|title=SXSW 2020 canceled due to coronavirus|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312115702/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|archive-date=2020-03-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|title=SXSW canceled: Austin officials end 2020 festival amid coronavirus concerns|website=KVUE|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308172426/https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] cancelled the rest of the event on March 11, that was slated to run until March 22. It was confirmed that a resident from [[Montgomery County, Texas]] that was tested positive, attended the BBQ cook off at the rodeo on February 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2020/03/11/montgomery-county-patient-rodeo-bbq.html|title=Montgomery County coronavirus patient attended Houston rodeo BBQ cook-off, mayor says|website=American City Business Journals|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The attendance for the rodeo on February 28, was 77,632, with 73,433 of the visitors went to the \"World Championship Barb-B-Que Contest,\" where that person attended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/|title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February|website=KPRC-TV|date=March 12, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\nThe FIRST Robotics World Championship, slated to occur in Houston around mid-April, was canceled due to the Coronavirus, along with all the other FIRST Robotics Competitions in Texas. The Championship is one of the world's largest gatherings in competitive robotics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 Notice |url=https://firstintexas.org/covid-19-notice/ |website=FIRST In Texas}}</ref>\n\nAfter the announcement of the ban of gatherings of over 500 people on March 13 (in San Antonio), [[Fiesta San Antonio]] postponed their event to November 2020, that was originally slated for mid-April.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Schools===\n[[Houston Independent School District]], the state's largest school district, is among dozens of school districts extending their spring break, to help prevent of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"TTB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/fort-bend-houston-area-isds-suspend-classes-texas-over-coronavirus/|title=School districts across Texas suspend classes over coronavirus concerns, prepare for online learning|last=Swaby|first=Aliyya|date=March 12, 2020|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wisd.org/apps/news/article/1183978|title=District Closure|last=Cain|first=Bonnie|date=|website=Waxahachie Independent School District|language=en|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The closures are not without precedent, as many schools closed for two weeks during the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 flu]].<ref name=\"TTB\"/> Among the closures of school districts and universities across the state, Governor Greg Abbott on March 16, waived all [[State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness]] (STAAR) testing for the 2019\u201320 school year for public grade schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/article241199061.html|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott waives STAAR test requirements amid COVID-19 school closures|last=Weinberg|first=Tessa|date=March 16, 2020|website=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Governor Abbott issued an executive order that closed schools statewide until at least April 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott says tens of thousands of Texans could test positive for COVID-19 within weeks |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/19/texas-restaurants-bars-closed-greg-abbott/ |website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> On March 31, the Governor announced that schools in the state will continue to stay close until May 4.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott orders Texans to \"minimize\" nonessential activity outside their homes|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/31/greg-abbott-texas-executive-order-closures/|website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] and [[2020 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]], [[2019\u201320 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]] and [[2019\u201320 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Stars season|Dallas Stars]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeCamp |first1=Scott |title=NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Mlive.com |date=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Texas Department of State Health Services]]\n* [https://www.county.org/TAC/media/TACMedia/Legal/2020/COVID-19-Declaration-Information.pdf List of COVID-19-related county orders] from the Texas Association of Counties\n* [https://www.jw.com/coronavirus/texas-orders/ List of COVID-19-related city and county orders] by Jackson Walker\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Texas|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Texas]]\n[[Category:2020 in Texas|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Texas]]\n[[Category:Health in Texas]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Texas, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas\n| map1 = Map_of_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Texas_latest.svg\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1 =\n{{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location = [[Texas]], U.S\n| first_case = [[San Antonio]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date = January 2020\n| confirmed_cases= 3,346<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in Texas (Dashboard) |url=https://txdshs.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/ed483ecd702b4298ab01e8b9cafc8b83 |website=Texas Department of State Health Services |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases = 131\n| deaths = 46\n<!--As of March 30, 2020-->\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached the U.S. state of [[Texas]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Texas medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Panic buying in Texas in response to the coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|upright|Empty shelves from [[panic buying]] at the [[Sams Club]] in [[Lufkin, Texas]], on March 13, 2020.]]\nOn March 4, public health officials in [[Fort Bend County, Texas|Fort Bend County]] reported a presumptive positive test result in a man in his 70s who had recently traveled outside the United States. The man was hospitalized in stable condition. The new case was the first in Texas outside of US nationals evacuated from Hubei Province and the ''Diamond Princess'' cruise ship to Joint Base San Antonio in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=Presumptive positive case of COVID-19 found in Fort Bend County, officials say|work=[[KTRK-TV]]|url=https://abc13.com/health/presumptive-case-of-covid-19-found-in-fort-bend-co/5977165/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=First case of 'presumptive positive' coronavirus confirmed in Fort Bend County|last1=Kamath|first1=Tulsi|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]|url=https://www.click2houston.com/news/local/2020/03/04/reports-first-case-of-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-fort-bend-county/}}</ref> On March 5, public health officials in Houston reported two confirmed cases in a man and a woman from northwest [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]]. Both cases are related to recent travel to Egypt.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Man, woman confirmed to be first cases of coronavirus in Harris County|last=Kamath|first=Tulsi|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]}}</ref> In the evening, an additional two cases, a man and a woman, were reported from Harris County also from the same travel group to Egypt. The woman is a staff member at [[Rice University]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=2 new presumptive positive coronavirus cases confirmed in Houston area, bringing total to 5; all cases connected to group who traveled to Egypt|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, three new cases were reported, one in [[Houston]] and two in Fort Bend County. All cases were part of a group that had traveled together to Egypt. This brought the Texas cases to 8, all in the Houston region.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/harris-county-coronavirus-total-outbreak-fort-bend-15111223.php|title=More coronavirus cases reported in Houston area|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbchealth.org/fort-bend-county-health-human-services-reports-2-additional-presumptive-positive-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-overall-total-to-3/|title=Fort Bend County Health & Human Services reports 2 additional presumptive positive cases of COVID-19, bringing overall total to 3|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> On March 9, [[Collin County]] reported 3 new presumptive cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |title=Parents, 3-year-old child test positive for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-10 |website=WFAA |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011925/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The patients were a married couple and their 3-year-old child who attended [[Frisco Independent School District|Frisco ISD]]. The man tested positive for the virus after visiting [[Silicon Valley]] in late February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |title=Frisco man tests 'presumptive positive' for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-09 |website=WFAA |language=en-US |url-status=live |access-date=2020-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202824/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |archive-date=2020-03-10 }}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] and [[Tarrant County, Texas|Tarrant County]] both announced one presumptive case in each county, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |title=First 'presumptive positive' cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Dallas, Tarrant counties |last=[[WFAA]] |website=WFAA |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011318/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On March 11, [[Houston]] mayor [[Sylvester Turner]] announced cancellation of the [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] after declaring the outbreak as a public health emergency.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Platoff |first1=Emma |title=Houston Rodeo called off as fears about new coronavirus continue to spread in Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311191252/https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first possible case of community spread was announced the same day, in a patient who had not traveled out of the state.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ackerman |first1=Todd |last2=Hensley |first2=Nicole |title='The tip of the iceberg': Coronavirus 'community spread' has started in Houston area |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Montgomery-County-patient-is-first-Houston-area-15123593.php |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lakewood Church]] in Houston, one of the nation's biggest mega-churches announced it was canceling in-person services till further notice.<ref>[https://www.khou.com/mobile/article/news/latest-coronavirus-updates-houston-texas-march-10-2020/285-1700bfab-1e04-4de4-a02f-ad4cb38e6ac3 Latest coronavirus updates: Lakewood Church suspends in-person services], KHOU (CBS affiliate), updated March 12, 2020.</ref> On March 12, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] announced five additional positive cases with one of the cases being the first instance of community spread in the [[North Texas]] area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ura |first1=Alexa |title=Dallas County officials say community spread of coronavirus has occurred in North Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/covid-19-community-spread-arrives-dallas-county/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> A day later, the cities of [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[San Antonio]], and [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], as well as [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]] and [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]] counties, announced confirmed cases. San Antonio also announced a ban of gatherings of 500 or more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tamplin |first1=Harley |title=What we know about the 44 coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/what-we-know-about-the-36-coronavirus-patients-in-texas/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |website=[[KXAN]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, [[University of Texas]] president [[Gregory L. Fenves]] announced that his wife Carmel had contracted Coronavirus after a trip to New York City. In an open letter to UT staff, faculty, and students, Fenves stated his wife began exhibiting flu-like symptoms after their trip, during which they attended several events with alumni and students, and was tested positive for COVID-19. Both Fenves, his wife, and an additional family member are in self-isolation, and the president has advised community members to follow CDC [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic#Prevention|preventive measures]] against the spread of the virus.<ref>Drew Knight [https://www.kvue.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/ut-austin-presidents-wife-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/269-13f8b439-61b2-4233-b426-69982ecf3aa7 University of Texas president's wife tests positive for coronavirus; UT President Gregory L. Fenves made the announcement in a letter to students on Friday.] March 13, 2020</ref> A presumptive case was reported and confirmed in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]]. The man is in his 40s and is in self-quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/news/2020/03/13/first-positive-case-coronavirus-covid-19-reported-el-paso/5048557002/|title=First presumptive positive case of coronavirus reported in El Paso area|date=March 13, 2020|work=El Paso Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Matagorda County officials announced the second positive case of COVID-19 in Matagorda County. The patient, a man in his late 90s, died Sunday evening at Matagorda Regional Medical Center with symptoms consistent with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite new |title=What we know about the 30 Houston Area coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://abc13.com/health/what-we-know-about-the-30-houston-area-coronavirus-cases/5999764/|accessdate=16 March 2020 |website=[[KTRK-TV|ABC13]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second death in Texas has been reported on March 17, of a resident of a retirement community in Arlington who died on Sunday, March 15.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/arlington-resident-dies-from-coronavirus-first-in-north-texas/2333046/ Arlington Resident Dies From Coronavirus, First in North Texas \u2013 NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]</ref>\n\nThe third death in Texas has been reported on March 18, of a resident in Plano who died in a local hospital on March 17.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/plano-man-infected-with-covid-19-dies-in-local-hospital/2333587/ Plano Man Infected With COVID-19 Dies in Local Hospital]</ref>\n\n[[Bell County, Texas]] announced its first death, a woman, on March 26.<ref>[https://www.fox44news.com/news/breaking-news/breaking-first-covid-19-death-reported-in-central-texas/#/questions/2574674 BREAKING: First COVID-19 death reported in Central Texas] Fox 44 News, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|300px|Texas is one of several states that have delegated [[stay-at-home order]] decisions to the county and municipal level.]]\n\nOn March 2, San Antonio Mayor [[Ron Nirenberg]] and [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]] both declared a \"local state of disaster and a public health emergency\" after an individual was mistakenly released from quarantine at Joint Base San Antonio by the CDC before a third test for coronavirus returned a positive result.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=Bexar County joins San Antonio in declaring public health emergency over coronavirus|last=Floyd|first=Jackson|url=https://www.kens5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bexar-county-coronavirus-public-health-emergency/273-788a002b-1b08-49d0-9a27-da639e6fed47|work=[[KENS]]|url-status=live}}</ref> The city subsequently petitioned the US government to extend the quarantine of US nationals at Joint Base San Antonio; the petition was denied by Judge [[Xavier Rodriguez]] in the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Texas]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=3 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio loses court battle to extend coronavirus quarantine, Public Health Emergency declaration continues|last=Ruiz|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.ktsa.com/san-antonio-loses-court-battle-to-extend-coronavirus-quarantine-public-health-emergency-declaration-continues/|work=[[KTSA]]|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio, Bexar County in battle with the CDC over evacuees|last1=Caruba|first1=Lauren|last2=Christenson|first2=Sig|url=https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303160332/https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|archive-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Both the city of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] and [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] have declared a \"local disaster of public health emergency\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/public-health-emergency-declared-in-dallas-county/2329709/|title=Dallas Mayor Speaks After Health Emergency Declared: 'We Will Get Through This'|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Greg Abbott]] declared a statewide disaster for all [[List of counties in Texas|counties in the state]]. He also announced the first drive-through testing facility in San Antonio, and will expand to other cities across the state.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=13 March 2020|access-date=13 March 2020|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott issues disaster declaration over coronavirus|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/13/texas-coronavirus-cases-state-emergency-greg-abbott/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/texas/article/Dallas-bans-large-gatherings-amid-coronavirus-15128474.php|first=Paul J |last=Weber |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title= Texas declares disaster; UT president's wife tests positive |date=2020-03-13|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Lieutenant Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] said that although this disease could take your life, workers should get back to work.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=24 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020|title='Repulsive': Outrage as Texas Lieutenant Gov. Says Seniors Willing to Risk Coronavirus Infection to Protect Economy|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/24/repulsive-outrage-texas-lieutenant-gov-says-seniors-willing-risk-coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Governor Abbott directed health care professionals to postpone surgeries that are not \"medically necessary\", as well as suspend regulations to allow hospitals to have more than one patient in a room.<ref name=\"no shelter\">{{cite news |last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Gov. Greg Abbott resists calls for statewide shelter-in-place; moves to expand hospital capacity|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/22/texas-shelter-in-place-coronavirus-cases/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Controversially, Attorney General [[Ken Paxton]] later indicated that this included [[abortion]]s (except for the life or health of the mother).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |title=Texas and Ohio Include Abortion as Medical Procedures That Must Be Delayed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/coronavirus-texas-ohio-abortion.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Abbott also stated that there will not be any statewide [[shelter in place]] anytime soon, due to the fact that more than 200 counties do not have any cases.<ref name=\"no shelter\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fine|first1=Julie|title=No Shelter in Place Order for Texas, Gov. Abbott Says|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/no-shelter-in-place-order-for-texas-gov-abbott-says/2337034/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Abbott leaves the decision to the local government to set stricter guidelines. Two hours later, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] ordered residents of [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] to shelter in place beginning 11:59{{nbsp}}pm on the following day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Nic |last2=Keomoungkhoun |first2=Nataly |last3=Branham |first3=Dana |last4=Steele |first4=Tom |title=Dallas County residents ordered to stay home as new shelter-in-place rules are put in place |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/public-health/2020/03/22/dallas-county-residents-ordered-to-stay-home-as-new-shelter-in-place-rules-are-put-in-place/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Dallas Morning News |date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A day later on March 23, [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bell County officials issue shelter in place order|url=https://www.kwtx.com/content/news/Bell-County-officials-issue-shelter-in-place-order-569036731.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KWTX-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar]],<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\">{{cite news |last1=Samuels|first1=Alex|title=Local leaders to announce stay-at-home orders in Austin and San Antonio|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/23/austin-travis-county-issue-stay-home-order-tuesday/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Brazos County, Texas|Brazos]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazos County issues two-week shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.theeagle.com/news/brazos-county-issues-two-week-shelter-in-place/article_54221a48-6d50-11ea-a67b-db9bc130c196.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Eagle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron County issues shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.krgv.com/news/watch-cameron-county-officials-provide-update-on-covid-19|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KRGV.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Hunt County, Texas|Hunt]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jefferies|first1=Kevin|title=Hunt County Issues Shelter-In-Place Disaster Declaration|url=https://www.ketr.org/post/hunt-county-issues-shelter-place-disaster-declaration|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Kert Radio|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Waco, McLennan County issue shelter-in-place order; county cases rise to 20|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/news/government/waco-orders-shelter-in-place-commissioners-extend-order-to-county/article_e6225b23-6d3f-5ce1-b6d5-7486ee1bebae.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Waco Tribune-Herald|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Garner|first=Erica|title=Stephens County becomes first in Big Country to give 'Shelter in Place' order|url=https://www.bigcountryhomepage.com/health/coronavirus/stephens-county-becomes-first-in-big-country-to-give-shelter-in-place-order/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Big Country Homepage|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> counties and the city of [[Forney, Texas|Forney]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Richards|first=Mathew|title=City of Forney orders Shelter in Place until April 8|url=https://www.inforney.com/local-news/city-of-forney-to-consider-shelter-in-place-order-during/article_76f1a00e-6d2b-11ea-a99c-fbf23c0b7775.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=InForney.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> issued a shelter in place for their communities. [[Collin County, Texas|Collin]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guerrero|first1=Maria|title=Collin County Expected to Issue Shelter-In-Place on Tuesday|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Powell|first1=Nick|title=Galveston County plans to issue shelter-in-place order due to coronavirus|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Galveston-County-plans-to-issue-shelter-in-place-15152206.php|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Houston Chronicle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Harris County, Texas|Harris]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scherer |first1=Jasper |title=Here are all the businesses exempted from Harris County's stay-at-home order |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Here-are-all-the-businesses-exempted-from-Harris-15154736.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> [[Travis County, Texas|Travis]]<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\"/><ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\">{{cite news|title=Austin, Travis and Williamson Counties Issue Shelter-In-Place Order Effective Tuesday|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/tx/austin/news/2020/03/24/austin--travis-county-officials-to-issue-shelter-in-place-order-tuesday|accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Spectrum News|date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Williamson County, Texas|Williamson]]<ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\"/> counties issued same measures on March 24. However, Collin County had more relaxed guidelines for their shelter in place order. Collin County's order stated that all businesses are essential and would be allowed to remain open as long as they followed social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|title=Collin County Judge Issues 'Stay Home, Work Safe' Measures, Businesses to Remain Open|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Lt. Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] declared that \u2018lots of grandparents\u2019 would be willing to die to save the economy for their grandchildren.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/dan-patrick-seniors-are-willing-to-die-to-save-economy.html Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick: \u2018Lots of Grandparents\u2019 Willing to Die to Save Economy for Grandchildren] By Matt Stieb, Intelligencer, 23 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Sixth Street Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|[[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|Sixth Street]] in Austin after all bars and restaurants were ordered closed]]\nOn March 13, [[Six Flags]] (based in Texas) suspended operations to all their properties (12) nationwide as well in Mexico, that were operating in the month of March, until the end of the month; these include the two Texas parks, [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] and [[Six Flags Over Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2020/03/13/saying-they-are-re-evaluating-coronavirus-risks-six-flags-over-texas-closes-park/|title=Saying They Are Re-Evaluating Coronavirus Risks, Six Flags Over Texas Closes Park|website=KTVT|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> [[Sea World San Antonio]] announced plans to close from March 16 to April 1, along with all [[Schlitterbahn]] waterparks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pettaway |first1=Taylor |last2=Express-News |first2=mySA com / San Antonio |title=Six Flags Fiesta Texas, Schlitterbahn Resorts, SeaWorld closing for March amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Six-Flags-Fiesta-Texas-is-closing-for-the-15129177.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=San Antonio Express-News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, [[H-E-B]] announced that all their stores across the state, will reduce the hours, to help restock items. This also includes their pharmacies and [[Central Market (Texas)|Central Market]] locations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernandez |first1=Emily |title=H-E-B changes store hours to restock shelves amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200314/h-e-b-changes-store-hours-to-restock-shelves-amid-coronavirus-concerns |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Austin American-Statesman |date=March 14, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The announcement comes a day after, when the company announced that its Houston area stores would be the only locations to implement changes to their operations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schuetz |first1=R. A. |last2=Takahashi |first2=Paul |title=Houston-area grocers rush to restock as coronavirus-related demand spikes |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Grocers-rush-to-restock-as-coronavirus-related-15129078.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\nFor the first time in the event's history, [[South by Southwest]] was cancelled as a result of local health concerns about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|title=SXSW 2020 canceled due to coronavirus|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312115702/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|archive-date=2020-03-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|title=SXSW canceled: Austin officials end 2020 festival amid coronavirus concerns|website=KVUE|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308172426/https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] cancelled the rest of the event on March 11, that was slated to run until March 22. It was confirmed that a resident from [[Montgomery County, Texas]] that was tested positive, attended the BBQ cook off at the rodeo on February 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2020/03/11/montgomery-county-patient-rodeo-bbq.html|title=Montgomery County coronavirus patient attended Houston rodeo BBQ cook-off, mayor says|website=American City Business Journals|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The attendance for the rodeo on February 28, was 77,632, with 73,433 of the visitors went to the \"World Championship Barb-B-Que Contest,\" where that person attended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/|title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February|website=KPRC-TV|date=March 12, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\nThe FIRST Robotics World Championship, slated to occur in Houston around mid-April, was canceled due to the Coronavirus, along with all the other FIRST Robotics Competitions in Texas. The Championship is one of the world's largest gatherings in competitive robotics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 Notice |url=https://firstintexas.org/covid-19-notice/ |website=FIRST In Texas}}</ref>\n\nAfter the announcement of the ban of gatherings of over 500 people on March 13 (in San Antonio), [[Fiesta San Antonio]] postponed their event to November 2020, that was originally slated for mid-April.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Schools===\n[[Houston Independent School District]], the state's largest school district, is among dozens of school districts extending their spring break, to help prevent of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"TTB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/fort-bend-houston-area-isds-suspend-classes-texas-over-coronavirus/|title=School districts across Texas suspend classes over coronavirus concerns, prepare for online learning|last=Swaby|first=Aliyya|date=March 12, 2020|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wisd.org/apps/news/article/1183978|title=District Closure|last=Cain|first=Bonnie|date=|website=Waxahachie Independent School District|language=en|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The closures are not without precedent, as many schools closed for two weeks during the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 flu]].<ref name=\"TTB\"/> Among the closures of school districts and universities across the state, Governor Greg Abbott on March 16, waived all [[State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness]] (STAAR) testing for the 2019\u201320 school year for public grade schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/article241199061.html|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott waives STAAR test requirements amid COVID-19 school closures|last=Weinberg|first=Tessa|date=March 16, 2020|website=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Governor Abbott issued an executive order that closed schools statewide until at least April 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott says tens of thousands of Texans could test positive for COVID-19 within weeks |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/19/texas-restaurants-bars-closed-greg-abbott/ |website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> On March 31, the Governor announced that schools in the state will continue to stay close until May 4.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott orders Texans to \"minimize\" nonessential activity outside their homes|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/31/greg-abbott-texas-executive-order-closures/|website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] and [[2020 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]], [[2019\u201320 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]] and [[2019\u201320 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Stars season|Dallas Stars]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeCamp |first1=Scott |title=NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Mlive.com |date=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Texas Department of State Health Services]]\n* [https://www.county.org/TAC/media/TACMedia/Legal/2020/COVID-19-Declaration-Information.pdf List of COVID-19-related county orders] from the Texas Association of Counties\n* [https://www.jw.com/coronavirus/texas-orders/ List of COVID-19-related city and county orders] by Jackson Walker\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Texas|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Texas]]\n[[Category:2020 in Texas|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Texas]]\n[[Category:Health in Texas]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:minor", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Texas"}
{"title_page": "Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 25, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\nThe '''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] that ran from 1990 to 1996.\n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992, a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|starring =\n|country = United States\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]]\n|first_aired = {{Start date|1990}}\n|last_aired = {{End date|1993}}\n|num_episodes = 69 (SportsChannel America)<br>24 (ESPN2)\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year deal with national cable network [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990 and aired on Monday nights. Reruns of the program, along with sporadic new episodes, continued airing on the network through 1993.\n\nIn 1991, Herb Abrams was owed money by Steve Ray and wrongly suspected that Ray was sleeping with his wife. On May 10, 1991 during a television taping at the [[New York Penta]], Abrams paid [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]] an extra $100 for the night to break Ray's nose during their match. Ray would years later claim this was a Worked Shoot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nIn 1995, existing episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 episodes re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]]<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref> between January and March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref> ESPN Classic started re-airing these episodes on February 4, 2009. [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990-1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990-1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)| ]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 25, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\nThe '''Universal Wrestling Federation''' (UWF) was a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] that ran from 1990 to 1996.\n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992, a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|starring =\n|country = United States\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]]\n|first_aired = {{Start date|1990}}\n|last_aired = {{End date|1993}}\n|num_episodes = 69 (SportsChannel America)<br>24 (ESPN2)\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year deal with national cable network [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990 and aired on Monday nights. Reruns of the program, along with sporadic new episodes, continued airing on the network through 1993.\n\nIn 1991, Herb Abrams was owed money by Steve Ray and wrongly suspected that Ray was sleeping with his wife. On May 10, 1991 during a television taping at the [[New York Penta]], Abrams paid [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]] an extra $100 for the night to break Ray's nose during their match. Ray would years later claim this was a Worked Shoot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nIn 1995, existing episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 episodes re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]]<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref> between January and March 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref> ESPN Classic started re-airing these episodes on February 4, 2009. [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990-1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990-1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)| ]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "name_user": "TheNewMinistry", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_Wrestling_Federation_(Herb_Abrams)"}
{"title_page": "Hans Christian Andersen Award", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Hans Christian Andersen Literature Award}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox award\n | name           = Hans Christian Andersen Award\n | image          = Hans Christian Andersen Medal.png\n | alt            = A golden medallion with an embossed image featuring a bust of Andersen.\n | description    = Outstanding and lasting contribution to [[children's literature]]\n | presenter      = [[International Board on Books for Young People]]\n | year           = {{start date and age|1956}}\n| most_awards = \n | website        = {{URL|http://www.ibby.org/awards-activities/awards/hans-christian-andersen-awards/|ibby.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Hans Christian Andersen Awards''' are two [[literary award]]s by the [[International Board on Books for Young People]] (IBBY), recognising one living author and one living illustrator for their \"lasting contribution to [[children's literature]]\".<ref name=about/> The writing award was inaugurated in 1956, the illustration award in 1966. The former is sometimes called the \"[[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] for children's literature\".\n\nThe awards are named after [[Hans Christian Andersen]], the 19th-century Danish author of [[fairy tales]], and each winner receives the Hans Christian Andersen Medaille, a gold medal with the bust of Andersen (see image). Medals are presented at the biennial IBBY Congress. The Patron of the Andersen Awards is Her Majesty Queen Margrethe II of Denmark and the awards are sponsored by Nami Island Inc.\n\n==Process==\nNational Sections of IBBY may nominate one author and one illustrator each and the Hans Christian Andersen Award Jury considers only those nominees. National Sections also nominate the ten distinguished, international Jury Members plus the Jury President. The shortlist of nominees is presented in January and the award winners are announced at the annual [[Bologna Children's Book Fair]], in March or April.\n\nThe selection criteria include the aesthetic and literary qualities of writing and illustrating as well as the ability to see things from the child's point of view and the ability to stretch the child's curiosity and imagination. The complete works of the author and of the illustrator will be taken into consideration.\n\n==Winners==\nSee also \"Hans Christian Andersen Award Winners 1956\u20132018\"<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2019|title=Hans Christian Andersen Award Winners 1956\u20132018|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/740854|journal=Bookbird: A Journal of International Children's Literature|language=en|volume=57|issue=4|pages=19\u201319|doi=10.1353/bkb.2019.0069|issn=1918-6983}}</ref>\n\nThe 2018 winners are [[Eiko Kadono]] (Japan) for writing and [[Igor Oleynikov]] (Russia) for illustration.<ref name=\"HCAA2018\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ibby.org/news-calendar/media-releases/2018-hcaa-winners/ |title=2018 HCAA Winners |publisher=[[International Board on Books for Young People]] |date=26 March 2018  |accessdate=11 April 2018 }}</ref> The runners-up are:\n\n* Writing: [[Marie-Aude Murail]] (France), [[Farhad Hasanzadeh]] (Iran), [[Joy Cowley]] (New Zealand), [[Ulf Stark]] (Sweden)\n* Illustration: [[Pablo Bernasconi]] (Argentina), [[Xiong Liang]] (China), [[Iwona Chmielewska]] (Poland), [[Albertine Zullo|Albertine]] (Switzerland)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibby.org/awards-activities/awards/hans-christian-andersen-awards/hcaa-2018/|title=HCAA 2018: IBBY official website|website=Ibby.org|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year !! colspan=\"2\" | Writing !! colspan=\"2\" | Illustration\n|-\n! Winner !! Country !! Winner !! Country\n|-\n|1956|| [[Eleanor Farjeon]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n|1958|| [[Astrid Lindgren]] || {{flag|Sweden}}\n|-\n|1960|| [[Erich K\u00e4stner]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|1962|| [[Meindert DeJong]] || {{flag|USA}}\n|-\n|1964|| [[Ren\u00e9 Guillot]] || {{flag|France}}\n|-\n|1966|| [[Tove Jansson]] || {{flag|Finland}} || [[Alois Carigiet]] || {{flag|Switzerland}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1968|| [[James Kr\u00fcss]] || {{flag|Germany}} || [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n|-\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Maria Sanchez-Silva]] || {{flag|Spain}} || ||\n|-\n|1970|| [[Gianni Rodari]] || {{flag|Italy}} || [[Maurice Sendak]] || {{flag|USA}}\n|-\n|1972|| [[Scott O'Dell]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Ib Spang Olsen]] || {{flag|Denmark}}\n|-\n|1974|| [[Maria Gripe]] || {{flag|Sweden}} || [[Farshid Mesghali]] || {{flag|Iran}}\n|-\n|1976|| [[Cecil B\u00f8dker]] || {{flag|Denmark}} || [[Tatjana Mawrina]] || {{flag|USSR}}\n|-\n|1978|| [[Paula Fox]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Svend Otto S.]] || {{flag|Denmark}}\n|-\n|1980|| [[Bohumil \u0158\u00edha]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}} || [[Suekichi Akaba]] || {{flag|Japan}}\n|-\n|1982|| [[Lygia Bojunga Nunes]] || {{flag|Brazil}} || [[Zbigniew Rychlicki]] || {{flag|Poland}}\n|-\n|1984|| [[Christine N\u00f6stlinger]] || {{flag|Austria}} || [[Mitsumasa Anno]] || {{flag|Japan}}\n|-\n|1986|| [[Patricia Wrightson]] || {{flag|Australia}} || [[Robert Ingpen]] || {{flag|Australia}}\n|-\n|1988|| [[Annie M. G. Schmidt]] || {{flag|Netherlands}} || [[Dusan K\u00e1llay]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n|-\n|1990|| [[Tormod Haugen]] || {{flag|Norway}} || [[Lisbeth Zwerger]] || {{flag|Austria}}\n|-\n|1992|| [[Virginia Hamilton]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Kv\u011bta Pacovsk\u00e1]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}{{efn|name=CZ1}}\n|-\n|1994|| [[Michio Mado]] || {{flag|Japan}} || [[J\u00f6rg M\u00fcller (artist)|J\u00f6rg M\u00fcller]] || {{flag|Switzerland}}\n|-\n|1996|| [[Uri Orlev]] || {{flag|Israel}} || [[Klaus Ensikat]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|1998|| [[Katherine Paterson]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Tomi Ungerer]] || {{flag|France}}\n|-\n|2000|| [[Ana Maria Machado]] || {{flag|Brazil}} || [[Anthony Browne (author)|Anthony Browne]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n|2002|| [[Aidan Chambers]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}} || [[Quentin Blake]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n|2004|| [[Martin Waddell]] || {{flag|Ireland}} || [[Max Velthuijs]] || {{flag|Netherlands}}\n|-\n|2006|| [[Margaret Mahy]] || {{flag|New Zealand}} || [[Wolf Erlbruch]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|2008|| [[J\u00fcrg Schubiger]] || {{flag|Switzerland}} || [[Roberto Innocenti]] || {{flag|Italy}}\n|-\n|2010|| [[David Almond]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}} || [[Jutta Bauer]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|2012|| [[Mar\u00eda Teresa Andruetto]] || {{flag|Argentina}} || [[Peter S\u00eds]] || {{flag|Czech Republic}}{{efn|name=CZ}}\n|-\n|2014|| [[Nahoko Uehashi]] || {{flag|Japan}} || [[Roger Mello]] || {{flag|Brazil}}\n|-\n|2016|| [[Cao Wenxuan]] || {{flag|China}} || [[Rotraut Susanne Berner]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|2018|| [[Eiko Kadono]] || {{flag|Japan}} || [[Igor Oleynikov]] || {{flag|Russia}}\n|}\n\n==Jury Presidents==\n[[Jella Lepman]] established the [[International Youth Library]] in Munich in 1949 and organised the 1952 conference \"International Understanding through Children's Books\" that led to the establishment of IBBY in Zurich in 1953. She served as Jury President for the first three Andersen Awards, 1956 to 1960, and remained on the jury until her death in 1970, as the President of IBBY and then as its honorary president. Current four-year terms cover two award cycles.<ref>[http://www.literature.at/viewer.alo?objid=14769&viewmode=fullscreen&scale=3.33&rotate=&page=114 \"Hans Christian Award jury members\"]. Glistrup, ed., pp. 119\u201324. Retrieved 2013-07-12.</ref>\n\n* Jella Lepman 1956-60 (Switzerland)\n* Jos\u00e9-Miguel de Azaola 1960-70 (Spain)\n* [[Virginia Haviland]] 1970-74 (USA)\n* Lucia Binder 1974-78 (Austria)\n* Dusan Roll 1978-82 (Czecho-Slovakia)\n* Patricia Crampton 1982-86 (UK)\n* [[Ana Maria Machado]] 1986-90 (Brazil)\n* Eva Glistrup 1990-94 (Denmark)\n* Peter Schneck 1994-98 (Austria)\n* Jay Heale 1998-2002 (South-Africa)\n* Jeffrey Garrett 2002-06 (USA)\n* Zohreh Ghaeni 2006-10 (Iran)\n* Mar\u00eda Jes\u00fas Gil Iglesia 2010-14 (Spain)\n* Patricia Aldana 2014-18 (Canada)\n*Junko Yokota 2020-22 (USA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibby.org/awards-activities/awards/hans-christian-andersen-awards/|title=Hans Christian Andersen Awards: IBBY official website|website=www.ibby.org|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nMachado subsequently won the Writing Award.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n* [[Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award]]\n* [[List of literary awards]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist |notes=\n\n{{efn|name=CZ1|1=\nPacovsk\u00e1 received the award one year before [[Czechoslovakia]] dissolved into its constituent states.\n}}\n{{efn|name=CZ|1=\nSis was nominated by the extant Czech Republic. He was born in the former [[Czechoslovakia]] and educated there in Applied Arts. He has been a U.S. citizen from 1982.\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs= \n<ref name=about>\n[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=273 \"Hans Christian Andersen Awards\"]. International Board on Books for Young People ('''IBBY'''). Retrieved 2012-08-20.</ref>\n}}\n*[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=308 \"Winners 1956\u20132012\"]. IBBY. Retrieved 2013-02-28.\n*Eva Glistrup, ed.; Patricia Crampton, transl. [http://www.literature.at/viewer.alo?objid=14769&page=1&viewmode=fullscreen ''The Hans Christian Andersen Awards, 1956\u20132002'']. IBBY. Copenhagen: [[Gyldendal]]. 2002. Hosted by [[Austrian Literature Online]] (''literature.at''). Retrieved 2013-02-28.\n*[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=1186 \"2012 Awards\"]. IBBY. Retrieved 2012-08-20.\n*[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=1315 \"2014 Awards\"]. IBBY. Retrieved 2013-07-14; 2014-03-18.\n*[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=1367 \"2014 Hans Christian Andersen Awards Shortlist\"]. IBBY. 17 March 2014. Retrieved 2014-03-18.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://exhibits.library.northwestern.edu/exhibits/hca/index.html \"The Hans Christian Andersen Collection at Northwestern: Illustrated Children's Books from Around the World: July 27th \u2013 September 9th, 2004\"] \u2014 multimedia exhibit by Northwestern University Library including much information about the HCA Award and the 2004 Illustration Award in particular\n \n{{Hans Christian Andersen Medal|state=expanded}}\n{{Hans Christian Andersen}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Children's literary awards]]\n[[Category:Danish literary awards]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1956]]\n[[Category:Hans Christian Andersen]]\n[[Category:Hans Christian Andersen Award for Illustration winners| ]]\n[[Category:Hans Christian Andersen Award for Writing winners| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Hans Christian Andersen Literature Award}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox award\n | name           = Hans Christian Andersen Award\n | image          = Hans Christian Andersen Medal.png\n | alt            = A golden medallion with an embossed image featuring a bust of Andersen.\n | description    = Outstanding and lasting contribution to [[children's literature]]\n | presenter      = [[International Board on Books for Young People]]\n | year           = {{start date and age|1956}}\n| most_awards = \n | website        = {{URL|http://www.ibby.org/awards-activities/awards/hans-christian-andersen-awards/|ibby.org}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Hans Christian Andersen Awards''' are two [[literary award]]s by the [[International Board on Books for Young People]] (IBBY), recognising one living author and one living illustrator for their \"lasting contribution to [[children's literature]]\".<ref name=about/> The writing award was inaugurated in 1956, the illustration award in 1966. The former is sometimes called the \"[[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] for children's literature\".\n\nThe awards are named after [[Hans Christian Andersen]], the 19th-century Danish author of [[fairy tales]], and each winner receives the Hans Christian Andersen Medaille, a gold medal with the bust of Andersen (see image). Medals are presented at the biennial IBBY Congress. The Patron of the Andersen Awards is Her Majesty Queen Margrethe II of Denmark and the awards are sponsored by Nami Island Inc.\n\n==Process==\nNational Sections of IBBY may nominate one author and one illustrator each and the Hans Christian Andersen Award Jury considers only those nominees. National Sections also nominate the ten distinguished, international Jury Members plus the Jury President. The shortlist of nominees is presented in January and the award winners are announced at the annual [[Bologna Children's Book Fair]], in March or April.\n\nThe selection criteria include the aesthetic and literary qualities of writing and illustrating as well as the ability to see things from the child's point of view and the ability to stretch the child's curiosity and imagination. The complete works of the author and of the illustrator will be taken into consideration.\n\n==Winners==\nSee also \"Hans Christian Andersen Award Winners 1956\u20132018\"<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2019|title=Hans Christian Andersen Award Winners 1956\u20132018|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/740854|journal=Bookbird: A Journal of International Children's Literature|language=en|volume=57|issue=4|pages=19\u201319|doi=10.1353/bkb.2019.0069|issn=1918-6983}}</ref>\n\nThe 2018 winners are [[Eiko Kadono]] (Japan) for writing and [[Igor Oleynikov]] (Russia) for illustration.<ref name=\"HCAA2018\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ibby.org/news-calendar/media-releases/2018-hcaa-winners/ |title=2018 HCAA Winners |publisher=[[International Board on Books for Young People]] |date=26 March 2018  |accessdate=11 April 2018 }}</ref> The runners-up are:\n\n* Writing: [[Marie-Aude Murail]] (France), [[Farhad Hasanzadeh]] (Iran), [[Joy Cowley]] (New Zealand), [[Ulf Stark]] (Sweden)\n* Illustration: [[Pablo Bernasconi]] (Argentina), [[Xiong Liang]] (China), [[Iwona Chmielewska]] (Poland), [[Albertine Zullo|Albertine]] (Switzerland)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibby.org/awards-activities/awards/hans-christian-andersen-awards/hcaa-2018/|title=HCAA 2018: IBBY official website|website=Ibby.org|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year !! colspan=\"2\" | Writing !! colspan=\"2\" | Illustration\n|-\n! Winner !! Country !! Winner !! Country\n|-\n|1956|| [[Eleanor Farjeon]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n|1958|| [[Astrid Lindgren]] || {{flag|Sweden}}\n|-\n|1960|| [[Erich K\u00e4stner]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|1962|| [[Meindert DeJong]] || {{flag|USA}}\n|-\n|1964|| [[Ren\u00e9 Guillot]] || {{flag|France}}\n|-\n|1966|| [[Tove Jansson]] || {{flag|Finland}} || [[Alois Carigiet]] || {{flag|Switzerland}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1968|| [[James Kr\u00fcss]] || {{flag|Germany}} || [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n|-\n| [[Jos\u00e9 Maria Sanchez-Silva]] || {{flag|Spain}} || ||\n|-\n|1970|| [[Gianni Rodari]] || {{flag|Italy}} || [[Maurice Sendak]] || {{flag|USA}}\n|-\n|1972|| [[Scott O'Dell]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Ib Spang Olsen]] || {{flag|Denmark}}\n|-\n|1974|| [[Maria Gripe]] || {{flag|Sweden}} || [[Farshid Mesghali]] || {{flag|Iran}}\n|-\n|1976|| [[Cecil B\u00f8dker]] || {{flag|Denmark}} || [[Tatjana Mawrina]] || {{flag|USSR}}\n|-\n|1978|| [[Paula Fox]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Svend Otto S.]] || {{flag|Denmark}}\n|-\n|1980|| [[Bohumil \u0158\u00edha]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}} || [[Suekichi Akaba]] || {{flag|Japan}}\n|-\n|1982|| [[Lygia Bojunga Nunes]] || {{flag|Brazil}} || [[Zbigniew Rychlicki]] || {{flag|Poland}}\n|-\n|1984|| [[Christine N\u00f6stlinger]] || {{flag|Austria}} || [[Mitsumasa Anno]] || {{flag|Japan}}\n|-\n|1986|| [[Patricia Wrightson]] || {{flag|Australia}} || [[Robert Ingpen]] || {{flag|Australia}}\n|-\n|1988|| [[Annie M. G. Schmidt]] || {{flag|Netherlands}} || [[Dusan K\u00e1llay]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}\n|-\n|1990|| [[Tormod Haugen]] || {{flag|Norway}} || [[Lisbeth Zwerger]] || {{flag|Austria}}\n|-\n|1992|| [[Virginia Hamilton]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Kv\u011bta Pacovsk\u00e1]] || {{flag|Czechoslovakia}}{{efn|name=CZ1}}\n|-\n|1994|| [[Michio Mado]] || {{flag|Japan}} || [[J\u00f6rg M\u00fcller (artist)|J\u00f6rg M\u00fcller]] || {{flag|Switzerland}}\n|-\n|1996|| [[Uri Orlev]] || {{flag|Israel}} || [[Klaus Ensikat]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|1998|| [[Katherine Paterson]] || {{flag|USA}} || [[Tomi Ungerer]] || {{flag|France}}\n|-\n|2000|| [[Ana Maria Machado]] || {{flag|Brazil}} || [[Anthony Browne (author)|Anthony Browne]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n|2002|| [[Aidan Chambers]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}} || [[Quentin Blake]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n|2004|| [[Martin Waddell]] || {{flag|Ireland}} || [[Max Velthuijs]] || {{flag|Netherlands}}\n|-\n|2006|| [[Margaret Mahy]] || {{flag|New Zealand}} || [[Wolf Erlbruch]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|2008|| [[J\u00fcrg Schubiger]] || {{flag|Switzerland}} || [[Roberto Innocenti]] || {{flag|Italy}}\n|-\n|2010|| [[David Almond]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}} || [[Jutta Bauer]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|2012|| [[Mar\u00eda Teresa Andruetto]] || {{flag|Argentina}} || [[Peter S\u00eds]] || {{flag|Czech Republic}}{{efn|name=CZ}}\n|-\n|2014|| [[Nahoko Uehashi]] || {{flag|Japan}} || [[Roger Mello]] || {{flag|Brazil}}\n|-\n|2016|| [[Cao Wenxuan]] || {{flag|China}} || [[Rotraut Susanne Berner]] || {{flag|Germany}}\n|-\n|2018|| [[Eiko Kadono]] || {{flag|Japan}} || [[Igor Oleynikov]] || {{flag|Russia}}\n|}\n\n==Jury Presidents==\nJella Lepman established the [[International Youth Library]] in Munich in 1949 and called the 1952 conference \"International Understanding through Children's Books\" that initiated IBBY. ([[:de:Jella Lepman|Jella Lepman]], German-language) She served as Jury President for the first three Andersen Awards, 1956 to 1960, and remained on the jury until her death in 1970, as the President of IBBY and then as its honorary president. Current four-year terms cover two award cycles.<ref>[http://www.literature.at/viewer.alo?objid=14769&viewmode=fullscreen&scale=3.33&rotate=&page=114 \"Hans Christian Award jury members\"]. Glistrup, ed., pp. 119\u201324. Retrieved 2013-07-12.</ref>\n\n* Jella Lepman 1956-60 (Switzerland)\n* Jos\u00e9-Miguel de Azaola 1960-70 (Spain)\n* [[Virginia Haviland]] 1970-74 (USA)\n* Lucia Binder 1974-78 (Austria)\n* Dusan Roll 1978-82 (Czecho-Slovakia)\n* Patricia Crampton 1982-86 (UK)\n* [[Ana Maria Machado]] 1986-90 (Brazil)\n* Eva Glistrup 1990-94 (Denmark)\n* Peter Schneck 1994-98 (Austria)\n* Jay Heale 1998-2002 (South-Africa)\n* Jeffrey Garrett 2002-06 (USA)\n* Zohreh Ghaeni 2006-10 (Iran)\n* Mar\u00eda Jes\u00fas Gil Iglesia 2010-14 (Spain)\n* Patricia Aldana 2014-18 (Canada)\n*Junko Yokota 2020-22 (USA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ibby.org/awards-activities/awards/hans-christian-andersen-awards/|title=Hans Christian Andersen Awards: IBBY official website|website=www.ibby.org|access-date=2020-01-02}}</ref>\n\nMachado subsequently won the Writing Award.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n* [[Astrid Lindgren Memorial Award]]\n* [[List of literary awards]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist |notes=\n\n{{efn|name=CZ1|1=\nPacovsk\u00e1 received the award one year before [[Czechoslovakia]] dissolved into its constituent states.\n}}\n{{efn|name=CZ|1=\nSis was nominated by the extant Czech Republic. He was born in the former [[Czechoslovakia]] and educated there in Applied Arts. He has been a U.S. citizen from 1982.\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs= \n<ref name=about>\n[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=273 \"Hans Christian Andersen Awards\"]. International Board on Books for Young People ('''IBBY'''). Retrieved 2012-08-20.</ref>\n}}\n*[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=308 \"Winners 1956\u20132012\"]. IBBY. Retrieved 2013-02-28.\n*Eva Glistrup, ed.; Patricia Crampton, transl. [http://www.literature.at/viewer.alo?objid=14769&page=1&viewmode=fullscreen ''The Hans Christian Andersen Awards, 1956\u20132002'']. IBBY. Copenhagen: [[Gyldendal]]. 2002. Hosted by [[Austrian Literature Online]] (''literature.at''). Retrieved 2013-02-28