{"title_page": "Maximum Ride (film)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Maximum Ride\n| image          =\n| caption        = \n| director       = Jay Martin\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Gary Binkow\n* Amee Dolleman\n}}\n| screenplay     = Angelique Hanus <br />Jesse Spears\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Maximum Ride]]''|[[James Patterson]]}}\n| starring       = Allie Marie Evans\n| music          = Bowie Dinkel<br>Kelvin Pimont\n| cinematography = Ed Wu\n| editing        = Joel Griffen\n| studio         = JP Entertainment<br>[[Studio 71]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]<ref name=\"THR\" />\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|08|30}}\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Maximum Ride''''' is a 2016 American [[science fiction film]] based on the [[Maximum Ride|novel of the same name]] by [[James Patterson]].  [[YouTube]] personality [[Jenna Marbles]] served as an executive producer of the film.<ref name=\"THR\" /><ref name=ew>{{cite web|last=Collis|first=Clark|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/27/maximum-ride-trailer-james-patterson|title=James Patterson adaptation Maximum Ride has wings: See the exclusive trailer|date=July 27, 2016|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walsh|first=Katie|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-maximum-ride-review-20160926-snap-story.html|title=Review Minimum budget yields minimal originality for young adult adaptation 'Maximum Ride'|date=September 29, 2016|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe movie sucks\n\n==Cast==\n* Allie Marie Evans as Max\n* [[Patrick Johnson (actor)|Patrick Johnson]] as Fang\n* Lyliana Wray as Angel\n* Luke Gregory Crosby as Ari\n* Gavin Lewis as Gazzy\n* Tetona Jackson as Nudge\n* [[Zayne Emory]] as Iggy\n* [[Peter O'Brien (actor)|Peter O'Brien]] as Jeb\n* [[Tina Huang]] as Dr. Rosen\n* Lillie Owers as Young Max\n\n==Reception==\nFrank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a negative review, writing \"You've seen it before, and done a lot better.\"<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web|last=Scheck|first=Frank|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/maximum-ride-review-934238|title='Maximum Ride': Film Review|date=September 30, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref><!-- only 1 reviews listed at Rotten Tomatoes. <ref>{{cite web|title=Maximum Ride|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/maximum_ride/|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref> -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0825283}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|maximum_ride}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by James Patterson]]\n[[Category:American science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films based on young adult literature]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Maximum Ride\n| image          =\n| caption        = \n| director       = Jay Martin\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Gary Binkow\n* Amee Dolleman\n}}\n| screenplay     = Angelique Hanus <br />Jesse Spears\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Maximum Ride]]''|[[James Patterson]]}}\n| starring       = Allie Marie Evans\n| music          = Bowie Dinkel<br>Kelvin Pimont\n| cinematography = Ed Wu\n| editing        = Joel Griffen\n| studio         = JP Entertainment<br>[[Studio 71]]\n| distributor    = [[Paramount Pictures]]<ref name=\"THR\" />\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|08|30}}\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Maximum Ride''''' is a 2016 American [[science fiction film]] based on the [[Maximum Ride|novel of the same name]] by [[James Patterson]].  [[YouTube]] personality [[Jenna Marbles]] served as an executive producer of the film.<ref name=\"THR\" /><ref name=ew>{{cite web|last=Collis|first=Clark|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/07/27/maximum-ride-trailer-james-patterson|title=James Patterson adaptation Maximum Ride has wings: See the exclusive trailer|date=July 27, 2016|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Walsh|first=Katie|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-mini-maximum-ride-review-20160926-snap-story.html|title=Review Minimum budget yields minimal originality for young adult adaptation 'Maximum Ride'|date=September 29, 2016|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nJeb rescues Max and the other children from the \"school\". His son Ari is left behind and presumed dead. In the present, Max is seen waking up from a dream; upon waking up, she encounters other members of the Flock.Iggy explains that they're running out of food, but Max wants to remain in the house. Angel is then captured by Erasers. \n\nThe Flock returns to the house and find the schools location. They deice that Fang and Max will go to rescue Angel, while the others,\u00a0 will remain home. Ari went to the house looking for Max, but they fight him off and escape, but Ari is left alive. \n\nMax and Fang stop to eat on a rooftop in Utah, where Max hears a girl being attacked. Fang tells Max not to intervene, but Max flies down to help before being shot in the shoulder. Fang smashes the gunman through a window; the girl, Ella, tells him that her mother is a doctor. They rush Max to the veterinary practice where Max is operated on.\n\nIggy, Gazzy and Nudge are walking through a small town. Iggy has a plan to meet up with the others at Lake Mead. Gazzy realizes Nudge is gone; they find her in a clothing store but have no idea that Ari is watching them. \n\nMax is given the all clear by the doctor, who points out a tracking chip in her shoulder and she rejoins Fang, who is angry that Max intervened but she insists it was the right thing to do. Izzy, Gazzy and Nudge then meet up with them and Max tells them about the tracking chip. They tell her about the house and about Ari. Max leaves the cabin and Ari confronts her and seems about to overpower her, but Fang starts fighting him before he and The Flock are captured.\n\nThey recover at the School, in cages, but are initially overjoyed to find Angel. Ari arrives and escorts Max to where Jeb is waiting. Max no longer trusts Jeb who tells her that she was created to help people and save the world. He shows her a hidden note and tells her that it was Ari's choice to become an Eraser. Max leaves the room and distracts Ari enough to steal his key card.\n\nMeanwhile, one of the whitecoats is secretly reporting on Jeb to another authority. The woman says that the Flock is expendable, but dangerous, and must be controlled.\n\nAri returns to the cage room to taunt Max, but Max has unlocked her cage and jumps on him. She hands the key card to Iggy before Ari chases her out of the room and the Flock escapes from their cages. Ari and the Erasers corner Max, only for the Flock to arrive with a bomb made by Gazzy. Max leaps out of the way and escapes safely. Jeb arrives, calling Ari's name. The Flock stands there, watching. Jeb pleads with Max, telling her she doesn't understand but she tells him the experiments over and opens her wings.\n\nAfterwards, the Flock walks through the woods. They pause and Max comforts Angel, only to collapse. She sees a vision of events throughout the movie, of child Ari moving to stab her with the scissors, and of New York City. When she awakens, she describes it to the Flock and they decide to go to New York City to look for more answers. The final shot is a video playing over and over again, of Max's final words to Jeb: \"The experiment's over.\"\n\n==Cast==\n* Allie Marie Evans as Max\n* [[Patrick Johnson (actor)|Patrick Johnson]] as Fang\n* Lyliana Wray as Angel\n* Luke Gregory Crosby as Ari\n* Gavin Lewis as Gazzy\n* Tetona Jackson as Nudge\n* [[Zayne Emory]] as Iggy\n* [[Peter O'Brien (actor)|Peter O'Brien]] as Jeb\n* [[Tina Huang]] as Dr. Rosen\n* Lillie Owers as Young Max\n\n==Reception==\nFrank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a negative review, writing \"You've seen it before, and done a lot better.\"<ref name=\"THR\">{{cite web|last=Scheck|first=Frank|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/maximum-ride-review-934238|title='Maximum Ride': Film Review|date=September 30, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref><!-- only 1 reviews listed at Rotten Tomatoes. <ref>{{cite web|title=Maximum Ride|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/maximum_ride/|access-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref> -->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0825283}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|maximum_ride}}\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by James Patterson]]\n[[Category:American science fiction films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films based on young adult literature]]\n", "name_user": "71.215.142.117", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePlot)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_Ride_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Barbara Creecy", "text_new": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix     = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                 = Barbara Creecy\n| native_name          = \n| native_name_lang     = \n| honorific-suffix     = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image                = Barbara Creecy.jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| smallimage           = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Creecy in 2014\n| office               = [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]]\n| deputy               = [[Maggie Sotyu]]\n| president            = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| term_start           = 30 May 2019\n| term_end             = \n| predecessor          = ''Position established''\n| successor             = \n| office1               = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| premier1              = \n| term_start1           = 22 May 2019\n| term_end1             = \n| predecessor1          = \n| successor1            = \n| constituency1        = [[Gauteng]]\n| office2              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Finance]]\n| premier2             = [[David Makhura]]\n| term_start2          = 23 May 2014\n| term_end2            = 25 May 2019\n| predecessor2         = [[Mandla Nkomfe]]\n| successor2           = [[Panyaza Lesufi]]\n| office3              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Education]]\n| premier3             = [[Nomvula Mokonyane]]\n| term_start3          = 8 May 2009\n| term_end3            = 23 May 2014\n| predecessor3         = [[Angie Motshekga]] \n| successor3           = [[Panyaza Lesufi]]\n| office4              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture]] \n| premier4             = [[Paul Mashatile]]<br>[[Mbhazima Shilowa]]\n| deputy4              = \n| term_start4          = 29 April 2004\n| term_end4            = 8 May 2009\n| predecessor4        = [[Mondil Gungubele]]\n| successor4          = Nelisiwe Mbatha-Mthimkhulu\n| office5             = Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n| leader5             =\n| term_start5         = 27 April 1994\n| term_end5           = 7 May 2019\n| predecessor5        = \n| successor5          = \n| office6            =\n| term_start6        = \n|constituency6       = \n| birthname          = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = South African\n| party              = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty         = [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| education          =\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Witwatersrand]]<br>[[University of London]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Barbara Dallas Creecy''' is a South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist. A member of the [[African National Congress]], she is currently serving as [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]], and a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]. She previously served as a Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]], having been elected in 1994. In 2004, she was named Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. She served until 2009 when she was appointed MEC for Education. Newly-elected Premier [[David Makhura]] moved Creecy to the Gauteng Finance portfolio in 2014.<ref>[http://www.gauteng.gov.za/government/departments/provincial-treasury/Pages/MEC-profile.aspx Ms Barbara Creecy MEC FOR FINANCE], ''Gauteng Digital Platform''. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Creecy was sworn in as a [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of Parliament]]. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] named her the new Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-in-full-cyril-ramaphosas-new-cabinet-in-his-own-words/ IN FULL | Cyril Ramaphosa's new cabinet, in his own words], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarbara Creecy was born in [[Johannesburg]]. She attended the [[University of Witwatersrand]] and obtained an Honours degree in Political Science. Later on, she completed a Master's degree in Public Policy and Management with the [[University of London]].<ref>[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/environment-forestry-and-fisheries-ministry/barbara-creecy-ms Barbara Creecy, Ms], ''South African Government''. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCreecy was an anti-apartheid activist and worked in the underground structures of the African National Congress whilst a student at the [[Witwatersrand University]]. She worked for the Civic Desk of the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] and soon joined an NGO that provided training and organisational development support to trade unions and community structures. She had previously been a member of the Provincial Executive Committee of the ANC.<ref>[https://www.smartprocurementworld.com/westerncape/2013/01/barbara-creecy.html Barbara Creecy MEC for Finance Gauteng Provincial Treasury], ''Smart Procurement World''. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nCreecy was one of the longest-serving Members of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature, having been elected in 1994. During her first two terms, she served as the Deputy Chief Whip as well as Chairperson of both the Social Development and Education Committees.<ref>Ndaba, Baldwin. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/sacp-lauds-gautengs-first-african-woman-finance-mec-24979210 SACP lauds Gauteng's 'first African woman' finance MEC], Gauteng, ''IOL'', 4 June 2019. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Premier [[Mbhazima Shilowa]] appointed her as MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. [[Paul Mashatile]] took over as [[Premier of Gauteng]] in 2008 and retained Creecy in her post.<ref>Grobler, Fienie. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-07-mashatile-elected-to-lead-gauteng Mashatile elected to lead Gauteng], ''Mail & Guardian'', 7 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>Rossouw, Mandy. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-04-which-way-will-he-swing Which way will he swing?], ''Mail & Guardian'', 4 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Creecy moved to the Education portfolio and served in that post until May 2014, when Premier [[David Makhura]] selected her as the new Gauteng Finance MEC.<ref>[https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/gautengs-new-mecs-announced Gauteng's new MECs announced], ''SA News'', 8 May 2009. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/the-new-gauteng-cabinet--david-makhura The new Gauteng cabinet \u2013 David Makhura]. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing the May 2019 elections, Creecy took office as a Member of the National Assembly. The media speculated that she would be appointed to the National Finance Department, as either Minister or Deputy Minister. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] appointed her to the post of Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>Haffajee, Ferial. [https://www.fin24.com/Economy/analysis-who-could-replace-nene-get-to-know-barbara-creecy-and-mondli-gungubele-20181008 ANALYSIS: Who could replace Nene? Get to know Barbara Creecy and Mondli Gungubele], ''Fin24'', 8 October 2018. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/fm/features/cover-story/2019-05-16-bets-for-the-new-cabinet/ Bets for the new cabinet], ''BusinesLIVE'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-29-cabinet-announcement-expected-on-wednesday-at-8pm-presidency-confirms Cabinet announcement expected on Wednesday evening, Presidency confirms], ''Mail & Guardian'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-breaking-ramaphosa-announces-cabinet/ Ramaphosa announces cabinet: Mabuza, Gordhan, Mboweni \u2013 and De Lille], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/from-patricia-to-pandor-here-is-ramaphosas-new-smaller-cabinet-20190529 From Patricia to Pandor \u2013 Here is Ramaphosa's new (smaller) Cabinet], ''News24'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/creecy-barbara/ People's Assembly profile]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/video/10367/barbara-creecy---1976--being-brought-up-by-a-single-mother---being-a-career-mom Barbara Creecy - 1976, being brought up by a single mother & being a career mom]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/08/behind-the-politics-creecy-on-student-activism-juggling-career-and-family-life BEHIND THE POLITICS: Creecy on student activism, juggling career and family life]\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creecy, Barbara}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix     = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                 = Barbara Creecy\n| native_name          = \n| native_name_lang     = \n| honorific-suffix     = [[Parliament of South Africa|MP]]\n| image                = Barbara Creecy.jpg\n| image_size           = 220px\n| smallimage           = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                  = \n| caption              = Creecy in 2014\n| office               = [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]]\n| deputy               = [[Maggie Sotyu]]\n| president            = [[Cyril Ramaphosa]]\n| term_start           = 30 May 2019\n| term_end             = \n| predecessor          = ''Position established''\n| successor             = \n| office1               = Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]\n| premier1              = \n| term_start1           = 22 May 2019\n| term_end1             = \n| predecessor1          = \n| successor1            = \n| constituency1        = [[Gauteng]]\n| office2              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Finance]]\n| premier2             = [[David Makhura]]\n| term_start2          = 23 May 2014\n| term_end2            = 25 May 2019\n| predecessor2         = [[Mandla Nkomfe]]\n| successor2           = [[Panyaza Lesufi]]\n| office3              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Education]]\n| premier3             = [[Nomvula Mokonyane]]\n| term_start3          = 8 May 2009\n| term_end3            = 23 May 2014\n| predecessor3         = [[Angie Motshekga]] \n| successor3           = [[Panyaza Lesufi]]\n| office4              = [[Government of Gauteng|Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture]] \n| premier4             = [[Paul Mashatile]]<br>[[Mbhazima Shilowa]]\n| deputy4              = \n| term_start4          = 2004\n| term_end4            = 8 May 2009\n| predecessor4        = ''Unknown''\n| successor4          = Nelisiwe Mbatha-Mthimkhulu\n| office5             = Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]]\n| leader5             =\n| term_start5         = 27 April 1994\n| term_end5           = 7 May 2019\n| predecessor5        = \n| successor5          = \n| office6            =\n| term_start6        = \n|constituency6       = \n| birthname          = \n| birth_date         = \n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         =  \n| death_place        = \n| citizenship        =\n| nationality        = South African\n| party              = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty         = [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]]\n| spouse             = \n| partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations          = \n| children           = \n| residence          = \n| education          =\n| alma_mater         = [[University of Witwatersrand]]<br>[[University of London]]\n| occupation         = \n| profession         = Politician\n| known_for          = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| website            = \n}}\n'''Barbara Dallas Creecy''' is a South African politician and previous anti-apartheid activist. A member of the [[African National Congress]], she is currently serving as [[Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries]], and a Member of the [[National Assembly of South Africa]]. She previously served as a Member of the [[Gauteng Provincial Legislature]], having been elected in 1994. In 2004, she was named Gauteng MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. She served until 2009 when she was appointed MEC for Education. Newly-elected Premier [[David Makhura]] moved Creecy to the Gauteng Finance portfolio in 2014.<ref>[http://www.gauteng.gov.za/government/departments/provincial-treasury/Pages/MEC-profile.aspx Ms Barbara Creecy MEC FOR FINANCE], ''Gauteng Digital Platform''. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Creecy was sworn in as a [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of Parliament]]. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] named her the new Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-in-full-cyril-ramaphosas-new-cabinet-in-his-own-words/ IN FULL | Cyril Ramaphosa's new cabinet, in his own words], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 29 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBarbara Creecy was born in [[Johannesburg]]. She attended the [[University of Witwatersrand]] and obtained an Honours degree in Political Science. Later on, she completed a Master's degree in Public Policy and Management with the [[University of London]].<ref>[https://www.gov.za/about-government/contact-directory/environment-forestry-and-fisheries-ministry/barbara-creecy-ms Barbara Creecy, Ms], ''South African Government''. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nCreecy was an anti-apartheid activist and worked in the underground structures of the African National Congress whilst a student at the [[Witwatersrand University]]. She worked for the Civic Desk of the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] and soon joined an NGO that provided training and organisational development support to trade unions and community structures. She had previously been a member of the Provincial Executive Committee of the ANC.<ref>[https://www.smartprocurementworld.com/westerncape/2013/01/barbara-creecy.html Barbara Creecy MEC for Finance Gauteng Provincial Treasury], ''Smart Procurement World''. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nCreecy was one of the longest-serving Members of the Gauteng Provincial Legislature, having been elected in 1994. During her first two terms, she served as the Deputy Chief Whip as well as Chairperson of both the Social Development and Education Committees.<ref>Ndaba, Baldwin. [https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/sacp-lauds-gautengs-first-african-woman-finance-mec-24979210 SACP lauds Gauteng's 'first African woman' finance MEC], Gauteng, ''IOL'', 4 June 2019. Retrieved on 28 July 2019.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Premier [[Mbhazima Shilowa]] appointed her as MEC for Sports, Recreation, Arts and Culture. [[Paul Mashatile]] took over as [[Premier of Gauteng]] in 2008 and retained Creecy in her post.<ref>Grobler, Fienie. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-07-mashatile-elected-to-lead-gauteng Mashatile elected to lead Gauteng], ''Mail & Guardian'', 7 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>Rossouw, Mandy. [https://mg.co.za/article/2008-10-04-which-way-will-he-swing Which way will he swing?], ''Mail & Guardian'', 4 October 2008. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Creecy moved to the Education portfolio and served in that post until May 2014, when Premier [[David Makhura]] selected her as the new Gauteng Finance MEC.<ref>[https://www.sanews.gov.za/south-africa/gautengs-new-mecs-announced Gauteng's new MECs announced], ''SA News'', 8 May 2009. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.politicsweb.co.za/archive/the-new-gauteng-cabinet--david-makhura The new Gauteng cabinet \u2013 David Makhura]. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\nFollowing the May 2019 elections, Creecy took office as a Member of the National Assembly. The media speculated that she would be appointed to the National Finance Department, as either Minister or Deputy Minister. On 29 May 2019, President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] appointed her to the post of Minister of Environment, Forestry and Fisheries.<ref>Haffajee, Ferial. [https://www.fin24.com/Economy/analysis-who-could-replace-nene-get-to-know-barbara-creecy-and-mondli-gungubele-20181008 ANALYSIS: Who could replace Nene? Get to know Barbara Creecy and Mondli Gungubele], ''Fin24'', 8 October 2018. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.businesslive.co.za/fm/features/cover-story/2019-05-16-bets-for-the-new-cabinet/ Bets for the new cabinet], ''BusinesLIVE'', 16 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2019-05-29-cabinet-announcement-expected-on-wednesday-at-8pm-presidency-confirms Cabinet announcement expected on Wednesday evening, Presidency confirms], ''Mail & Guardian'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2019-05-29-breaking-ramaphosa-announces-cabinet/ Ramaphosa announces cabinet: Mabuza, Gordhan, Mboweni \u2013 and De Lille], ''TimesLIVE'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/from-patricia-to-pandor-here-is-ramaphosas-new-smaller-cabinet-20190529 From Patricia to Pandor \u2013 Here is Ramaphosa's new (smaller) Cabinet], ''News24'', 29 May 2019. Retrieved 30 May 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/creecy-barbara/ People's Assembly profile]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/video/10367/barbara-creecy---1976--being-brought-up-by-a-single-mother---being-a-career-mom Barbara Creecy - 1976, being brought up by a single mother & being a career mom]\n*[https://ewn.co.za/2019/08/08/behind-the-politics-creecy-on-student-activism-juggling-career-and-family-life BEHIND THE POLITICS: Creecy on student activism, juggling career and family life]\n{{Current MPs of South Africa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Creecy, Barbara}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:University of the Witwatersrand alumni]]\n[[Category:White South African anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:Women government ministers of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "Found her predecessor!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbara_Creecy"}
